# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agriculture-in-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The **Aberdeen Angus**, sometimes simply **Angus**, is a Scottish breed of small beef cattle.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] It derives from cattle native to the counties of Aberdeen, Banff, Kincardine and Angus in north-eastern Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] In 2018, it accounted for over 17% of the beef production in the United Kingdom.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The Angus is naturally polled and solid black or red; the udder may be white.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The cattle have been exported to many countries of the world; there are large populations in Australia, Canada, New Zealand, South America and the United States, where it has developed into two separate and distinct breeds, the American Angus and the Red Angus.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] In some countries it has been bred to be taller than the native Scottish stock.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] Its conservation status worldwide is "not at risk"; in the United Kingdom the original Native Aberdeen Angus – cattle not influenced by cross-breeding with imported stock – is listed by the Rare Breeds Survival Trust as "at risk".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] For some time before the 1800s, the hornless cattle in Angus were called "Angus Doddies", while those in the historic province of Buchan (later part of Aberdeenshire) were known as "Buchan Humlies", both "doddie" and "humlie" meaning “polled”.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] In 1824, William McCombie of Tillyfour, later the Member of Parliament for West Aberdeenshire, began to improve the stock and is regarded today as the father of the breed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The breed was officially recognised in 1835, and was initially registered together with the Galloway in the Polled Herd Book.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The cattle became commonplace throughout the British Isles in the mid-twentieth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] As stated in the fourth volume of the Herd Book of the UK's Angus, this breed was introduced to Argentina in 1879 when "*Don* Carlos Guerrero" imported one bull and two cows for his *Estancia* "Charles" located in Juancho, Partido de General Madariaga, Provincia de Buenos Aires.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The bull was born on 19 April 1878; named "Virtuoso 1626" and raised by Colonel Ferguson.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The cows were named "Aunt Lee 4697" raised by J.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] Walker and were both born in 1878, on 31 January and 23 April respectively.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] Angus cattle were first introduced to Van Diemen's Land (now Tasmania) in the 1820s, and to the southern mainland in 1840.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The breed is now found in all Australian states and territories with 62000 calves registered with Angus Australia in 2010.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] In 1876 William Brown, a professor of agriculture and then superintendent of the experimental farm at Guelph, Ontario, was granted permission by the government of Ontario to purchase Aberdeen Angus cattle for the Ontario Agricultural College.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The herd comprised a yearling bull, Gladiolus, and a cow, Eyebright, bred by the Earl of Fife and a cow, Leochel Lass 4th, bred by R.O.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] On 12 January 1877, Eyebright gave birth to a calf, sired by Sir Wilfrid.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] It was the first to be born outside of Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The OAC went on to import additional bulls and cows, eventually began selling Aberdeen Angus cattle in 1881.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] On 17 May 1873, George Grant brought four Angus bulls, without any cows, to Victoria, Kansas.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] These were seen as unusual as the normal American cattle consisted of Shorthorns and Longhorns, and the bulls were used only in crossbreeding; however, the farmers noticed the good qualities of these bulls, and afterwards many more cattle of both sexes were imported.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] On 21 November 1883, the American Angus Association was founded in Chicago, Illinois.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The first herd book was published in March 1885.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] At this time, both red and black animals were registered without distinction. in 1917, it barred the registering of red and other coloured animals in an effort to promote a solid black breed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The Red Angus Association of America was founded in 1954 by breeders of Red Angus cattle.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] It was formed because the breeders had had their cattle struck off the herd book for not conforming to the changed breed standard regarding colour.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] A separate breed was cross bred in Germany called the German Angus.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] It is a cross between the Angus and several different cattle such as the German Black Pied Cattle, Gelbvieh, and Fleckvieh.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The cattle are usually larger than the Angus and appear in black and red colours.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] Because of their native environment, the cattle are very hardy and can survive the Scottish winters, which are often harsh, with snowfall and storms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] Cows weigh about 550 kilograms (1,210 lb) and bulls some 850 kilograms (1,870 lb).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] Bulls may be used on dairy cows to produce a beef calf.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The cattle are naturally polled and may be either black or red.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] They reach maturity earlier than some other native British breeds such as the Hereford or North Devon.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The cattle have a large muscle content and are regarded as medium-sized.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] In Japan the meat is prized for its marbling.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] Among the recessive genetic defects that can affect the cattle are: arthrogryposis multiplex ("curly calf"); neuropathic hydrocephalus ("water head"); contractural arachnodactyly or "fawn calf syndrome"; dwarfism; osteoporosis; and notomelia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The Aberdeen Angus is reared principally for beef.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] Bulls are used extensively as terminal sires on cows of other breeds – particularly dairy breeds – to produce cross-bred beef calves.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] The meat can be marketed as superior due to its marbled appearance.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] Bulls can also be used to transmit characteristics including the polled gene (for ease of handling) and – with the aim of lowering the incidence of dystocia – the easy calving of cows.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/aberdeen-angus] Many modern breeds derive from the Aberdeen Angus or from its American derivatives, the American Angus and Red Angus of the United States.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/adam-smith-school-of-economics-and-finance] The first chair of accountancy was established within the Faculty of Law in 1925, with Bachelor of Accounting and Master of Accounting degrees being introduced in 1968.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/adam-smith-school-of-economics-and-finance] In 1971, the Scottish Business School (SBS) was established as a collaboration between the universities of Edinburgh, Glasgow and Strathclyde.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/adam-smith-school-of-economics-and-finance] The SBS launched a part-time MBA at Glasgow University in 1976.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/adam-smith-school-of-economics-and-finance] In 1978, Andrew Thomson was appointed Professor of Business Policy in Glasgow's recently established Department of Management Studies.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/adam-smith-school-of-economics-and-finance] The business school was established in 1986.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/adam-smith-school-of-economics-and-finance] The school continues research in international finance, international economics and macroeconomics.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/adam-smith-school-of-economics-and-finance] As of 2024, the business school offered four undergraduate and 35 postgraduate degrees (including PhDs) and is one of few institutions holding triple accreditation from AACSB, AMBA and EQUIS.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/adam-smith-school-of-economics-and-finance] To commemorate 300 years since the birth of Adam Smith in 2023, students of the school designed a school tartan which is recognised in the Scottish Register of Tartans.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/adam-smith-school-of-economics-and-finance] The School has 11 research clusters, including: accounting; entrepreneurship, development and political economy; finance; human resource management and organisational behaviour; international business and enterprise; macroeconomics; marketing and microeconomics.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] As feudal distinctions declined in the early modern era, the barons and tenants-in-chief merged to form a new identifiable group, the lairds.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] With the yeomen, these heritors were the major landholding orders.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Others with property rights included husbandmen and free tenants.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Many young people left home to become domestic and agricultural servants.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The English invasions of the 1640s had a profound impact on the Scottish economy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Under the Commonwealth, the country was relatively highly taxed, but gained access to English markets.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] After the Restoration customs duties with England were re-established.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Economic conditions were generally favourable, as land owners promoted better tillage and cattle-raising.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] After the Union of 1707 there was a conscious attempt to improve agriculture among the gentry and nobility.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Introductions included the English plough, foreign grasses, rye grass and clover, turnips and cabbages.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Lands were enclosed, displacing the run rig system and free pasture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Marshes were drained, lime was put down, roads built, woods planted, drilling and sowing and crop rotation were introduced.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The introduction of the potato to Scotland in 1739 greatly improved the diet of the peasantry.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The resulting Lowland Clearances saw the eviction of hundreds of thousands of cottars and tenant farmers in central and southern Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Scotland is roughly half the size of England and Wales and has approximately the same amount of coastline, but only between a fifth and a sixth of the amount of the arable or good pastoral land, under 60 metres above sea level, and most of this is located in the south and east.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The early modern era saw the impact of the Little Ice Age, of colder and wetter weather, which peaked towards the end of the seventeenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] In 1564 there were thirty-three days of continual frost, with rivers and lochs freezing over.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] This reduced the altitude at which crops could be grown and shortened the growing season by up to two months in extreme years.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Almost half the years in the second half of the sixteenth century saw local or national scarcity, necessitating the shipping of large quantities of grain from the Baltic, referred to as Scotland's "emergency granary".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] This was particularly from Poland through the port of Danzig, but later Königsberg and Riga, shipping Russian grain, and Swedish ports, would become important.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The trade was so significant that Scottish colonies were established in these ports.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] While the feudal tenures of barons were increasingly nominal local tenants-in-chief, who held legally held their land directly from the king and who by the sixteenth century were often the major local landholders in an area, grew in significance.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] As feudal distinctions declined, the barons and tenants-in-chief merged to form a new identifiable group, the lairds, roughly equivalent to the English gentlemen.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Below the lairds were a variety of groups, often ill-defined.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] These included yeomen, later characterised by Walter Scott as "bonnet lairds", often owning substantial land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The practice of feuing (by which a tenant paid an entry sum and an annual feu duty, but could pass the land on to their heirs) meant that the number of people holding heritable possession of lands, which had previously been controlled by the church or nobility, expanded.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] These and the lairds probably numbered about 10,000 by the seventeenth century and became what the government defined as heritors, on whom the financial and legal burdens of local government increasingly fell.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Below the substantial landholders were those engaged in subsistence agriculture, who made up the majority of the working population.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Those with property rights included husbandmen, lesser landholders and free tenants.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Below them were the cottars, who often shared rights to common pasture, occupied small portions of land and participated in joint farming as hired labour.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Farms also might have grassmen, who had rights only to grazing.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] By the early modern era in Lowland rural society, as in England, many young people, both male and female, left home to become domestic and agricultural servants.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Women acted as an important part of the workforce.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] As well as moving away from their families as farm servants, married women worked with their husbands around the farm, taking part in all the major agricultural tasks.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] They had a particular role as shearers in the harvest, forming most of the reaping team of the *bandwin*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The most common system was based on infield and outfield agriculture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The infield was the best land, close to housing.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] It was farmed continuously and most intensively, receiving most of the manure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Crops were usually bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The more extensive outfield was used largely for oats.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] It was fertilised from the overnight folding of cattle in the summer and was often left fallow to recover its fertility.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] In fertile regions the infield could be extensive, but in the uplands it might be small, surrounded by large amounts of outfield.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] In coastal areas fertiliser included seaweed and around the major burghs urban refuse was used.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Yields were fairly low, often around three times the quantity of seed sown, although they could reach twice that yield on some infields.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The area of arable land farmed by a family was notionally suitable for two or three plough teams, allocated in runrigs.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Runrigs, were a ridge and furrow pattern, similar to that used in parts of England, with alternating "runs" (furrows) and "rigs" (ridges).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] They usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land, helping to offset some of the problems of extreme weather conditions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective on heavy soils and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] They were usually pulled by a team of eight oxen, which would have taken four men to operate and only covered half an acre a day.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Pasture was often accessed by shieling-grounds, with shelters made of stone or turf, used for the grazing of cattle in summer.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] These would often be distant from the main settlements in the Lowlands, but might be relatively close in the more remote Highlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] All farms combined livestock with arable farming, with cattle and sheep and goats in parts of the Highlands and all farms growing some grain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] However, there was some specialisation, with arable most important in the East and there was a tradition of sheep farming in the eastern Borders dating back to the arrival of new monastic orders in the twelfth century, which continued after the secularisation of the monasteries.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] In the early seventeenth century famine was relatively common, with four periods of famine prices between 1620 and 1625.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The English invasions of the 1640s had a profound impact on the Scottish economy, with the destruction of crops and the disruption of markets resulting in some of the most rapid price rises of the century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] After the Restoration the formal frontier with England was re-established, along with its customs duties.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Economic conditions were generally favourable from 1660 to 1688, as land owners promoted better tillage and cattle-raising.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Arable farming grew in the Lowlands, particularly around the growing urban centres like Edinburgh.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Agricultural improvement began in the late seventeenth century in the Lothians and central Scotland, with the use of lime to combat the acidity of the soil, trees were planted, new crops introduced including sown grass and the rotation of crops.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Three acts of parliament passed in 1695 allowed the consolidation of runrigs and the division of commonties and common pasture and small scale enclosures began to be carried out.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Highlanders had been droving cattle on the hoof to the Lowlands since at least the sixteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] By the 1680s the trade had expanded to the larger English markets.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Cattle were crossed with larger Irish breeds and large parks were constructed by Galloway landholders to hold and fatten cattle.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] By the end of the century the drovers roads had become established, stretching down from the Highlands through south-west Scotland to north-east England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] From there some were driven to Norfolk to be fattened before being slaughtered in Smithfield for the London population.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Specialisation continued, with the increasing commercialisation of sheep farming in the Borders as English markets opened up after the Union of Crowns in 1603 and dairy becoming a feature of farming in the western Lowlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The closing decade of the seventeenth century saw the generally favourable economic conditions that had dominated since the Restoration come to an end.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] There was a slump in trade with the Baltic and France from 1689 to 1691, caused by French protectionism and changes in the Scottish cattle trade, followed by four years of failed harvests (1695, 1696 and 1698-9), known as the "seven ill years".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The result was severe famine and depopulation, particularly in the north.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The famines of the 1690s were seen as particularly severe, partly because famine had become relatively rare in the second half of the seventeenth century, with only one year of dearth (in 1674) and the shortages of the 1690s would be the last of their kind.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Climatic conditions began to improve in the early eighteenth century, although there were still bad years, like that of 1739–41.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Increasing contacts with England after the Union of 1707 led to a conscious attempt to improve agriculture among the gentry and nobility.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The Society of Improvers was founded in 1723, including in its 300 members dukes, earls, lairds and landlords.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Before the eighteenth century English books on husbandry had been available or reprinted in Scotland, but in the eighteenth century there were increasing numbers of titles published by Scottish authors in Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] In the first half of the century these changes were limited to tenanted farms in East Lothian and the estates of a few enthusiasts, such as John Cockburn and Archibald Grant.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Not all were successful, with Cockburn driving himself into bankruptcy, but the ethos of improvement spread among the landed classes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The English plough, rye grass and clover, turnips and cabbages were introduced; lime was put down, marshes were drained, roads built and woods planted.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Drilling and sowing and crop rotation were introduced.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Enclosures began to displace the runrig system and free pasture, creating the landscape of largely rectangular fields that characterises the Lowland Scottish landscape today.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] New farm buildings, often based on designs in patterns books, replaced the fermtoun and regional diversity was replaced with a standardisation of building forms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Smaller farms retained the linear outline of the longhouse, with dwelling house, barn and byre in a row, but in larger farms a three- or four-sided layout became common, separating the dwelling house from barns and servants quarters.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] There were also organisational changes that would have long term consequences, including the commutation of payments in kind for those in money, the granting of longer leases and the consolidation of smaller holdings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Tens of thousands of others emigrated to Canada or the United States, finding opportunities there to own and farm their own land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters allowed cultivation at much greater heights and made land more productive.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open-field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism from the twelfth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for oats.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] New monastic orders such as the Cistercians became major landholders and sheep farmers, particularly in the Borders where they were organised in granges.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the late Medieval period, most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams, allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, known as husbandmen.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised for meat.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The rural economy appears to have boomed in the thirteenth century and in the immediate aftermath of the Black Death was still buoyant, but by the 1360s there was a severe falling off in incomes to be followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This made marginal pastoral farming and fishing, the key factors in the pre-modern economy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Its east Atlantic position means that it has moderate rainfall: today about 700 mm per year in the east and over 1,000 mm in the west.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This encouraged the spread of blanket peat bog, the acidity of which, combined with high level of wind and salt spray, made most of the western islands treeless.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The existence of hills, mountains, quicksands and marshes made agriculture and internal communication difficult.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The early Middle Ages, from the fifth century to the tenth century, were a period of climate deterioration, with a drop in temperature and an increase in rainfall, resulting in more land becoming unproductive.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] With a lack of significant transport links and wider markets, most farms had to produce a self-sufficient diet of meat, dairy products and cereals, supplemented by hunter-gathering.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The climate meant that more oats and barley were grown than wheat.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The evidence of bones indicates that cattle were by far the most important domesticated animal, followed by pigs, sheep and goats, while domesticated fowl were very rare.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Christian missionaries from Ireland may have changed agricultural practice, bringing innovations such as the horizontal watermill and mould board ploughs, which were more effective in turning the soil.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters of the Medieval Warm Period allowed cultivation at much greater heights above sea level and made land more productive.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas in the south and east than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The feudalism introduced under David I, particularly in the east and south where the crown's authority was greatest, saw the placement of baronial lordships.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Land was now held from the king, or a superior lord, in exchange for loyalty and forms of service that were usually military.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Barons, who held feudal tenures, had the right to hold baronial courts, which could deal with matters of land ownership.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the imposition of feudalism continued to sit beside the existing systems of landholding and tenure and it is not clear how this change impacted on the lives of the ordinary free and unfree workers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In places, feudalism may have tied workers more closely to the land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the predominantly pastoral nature of Scottish agriculture may have made the imposition of a manorial system, based on the English model, impracticable in some areas.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Obligations appear to have been limited to occasional labour service, seasonal renders of food, hospitality and money rents.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually included supplying oxen for ploughing the lord's land on an annual basis and the much resented obligation to grind corn at the lord's mill.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones, creating large tracts of land reserved for the leisure of the aristocracy and nobility.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were less rigorously enforced than in England, where the taking of wood and game were strictly forbidden, and all royal forests were on land already in the king's hands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The introduction of new monastic orders such as the Cistercians in this period also brought innovations in agriculture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Particularly in the Borders, their monasteries became major landholders, sheep farmers and producers of wool for the markets in Flanders.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were organised in granges, monastic farms run by lay brothers of the order.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Granges were theoretically within 30 miles of the mother monastery, so that those working there could return for services on Sundays and feast days.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were used for variety of purposes, including pastoral, arable and industrial production.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, to manage more distant assets in Ayrshire, Melrose Abbey used Mauchline as a "super grange", to oversee lesser granges.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Some abbeys like Melrose had at least 12,000 sheep in the late thirteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism and would continue until the eighteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This expanded from the use of small enclosed fields, which continued from the prehistoric era.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for largely for oats.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The main unit of land measurement in Scotland was the *davoch* (i.e.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This unit is also known as the "Scottish ploughgate".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In English-speaking Lothian, it was simply a ploughgate.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It may have measured about 104 acres (0.42 km2), divided into 4 *raths* or eight *oxgangs*, the area that eight oxen were said to be able to plough in one year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the fourteenth century most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, who were usually known as husbandmen or bonders.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The average amount of land used by a husbandman in Scotland, known as a husbandland, was 26 acres, or 2 oxgangs.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They would also have had a share of hay meadow and common pasture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Below the husbandmen, lesser landholders and free tenants, were the cottars, who often shared rights to common pasture, occupied small portions of land and participated in joint farming as hired labour.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Key crops included kale (for both humans and animals), and hemp and flax for cloth production.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised primarily for meat.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This was followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Towards the end of the period average temperatures began to reduce again, with the cooler and wetter conditions of the Little Ice Age limiting the extent of arable agriculture, particularly in the Highlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The early modern era saw the impact of the Little Ice Age, which peaked towards the end of the seventeenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The closing decade of the seventeenth century saw a slump, followed by four years of failed harvests, in what is known as the "seven ill years", but these shortages would be the last of their kind.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Introductions included haymaking, the English plough, new crops, crop rotation and encloses were introduced.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The resulting Lowland Clearances saw hundreds of thousands of cottars and tenant farmers from central and southern Scotland lose access to land and either become landless agricultural workers or emigrate to the growing industrial cities or elsewhere.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The later Highland Clearances involved the eviction of many traditional tenants as lands were enclosed, principally for sheep farming.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the first phase, many Highlanders were relocated as crofters, living on very small rented farms which required other employment to be found.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the twentieth century Scottish agriculture became more susceptible to world markets.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There were dramatic price rises in the First World War, but a slump in the 1920s and 1930s, followed by more rises in World War II.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In 1947 annual price reviews were introduced in an attempt to stabilise the market.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There was a drive in UK agriculture to greater production until the late 1970s, resulting in intensive farming.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There was increasing mechanisation and farming became less labour-intensive.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] UK membership of the European Economic Community from 1972 began a change in orientation for Scottish farming.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Some sectors became viable only with subsidies.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] A series of reforms to the CAP from the 1990s attempted to control over-production, limit incentives for intensive farming and mitigate environmental damage.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] A dual farm structure has emerged with agriculture divided between large commercial farms and small pluralised and diversified holdings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Roughly 79 per cent of Scotland’s total land area is under agricultural production.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Cereals accounted for 78 per cent of cropped land area (not total farmed area), while livestock numbers have been falling in recent years.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Around 15 per cent of the total land area of Scotland is forested, most in public ownership controlled by the Forestry Commission.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Total income from farming has been rising since the turn of the millennium.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Aquaculture production is focused on the West and North of the country.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Some farm businesses rely on sources of income other than from farming.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Scottish agriculture employs around 1.5 per cent of the workforce and contributes to around 1 per cent of the Scottish economy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The defining factor in the geography of Scotland is the distinction between the Highlands and Islands in the north and west and the Lowlands in the south and east.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The Highlands are further divided into the Northwest Highlands and the Grampian Mountains by the fault line of the Great Glen.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The Lowlands are divided into the fertile belt of the Central Lowlands and the higher terrain of the Southern Uplands, which included the Cheviot Hills, over which the border with England runs.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The Central Lowland belt averages about 50 miles in width, and contains most of the good quality agricultural land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland is half the size of England and Wales in area, but with its many inlets, islands and inland lochs, it has roughly the same amount of coastline at 4,000 miles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Only a fifth of Scotland is less than 60 metres above sea level.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland's soils are diverse for a relatively small country due to the variation in geology, topography, climate, altitude and land use history.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There are very productive arable soils in the east of the country, including some of the most productive for wheat and barley of anywhere in the world.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland's soils differ from much of the rest of the UK and Europe and they provide valuable habitats for wildlife and flora.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] They are largely naturally acidic in nature with high concentrations of organic carbon.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] They are predominantly coarse textured and often exhibit poor drainage.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The climate of Scotland is temperate and very changeable, but rarely extreme.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland is warmed by the North Atlantic Drift and given the northerly location of the country, experiences much milder conditions than areas on similar latitudes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Average temperatures are lower than in the rest of Great Britain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Western coastal areas of Scotland are warmer than the east and inland areas, due to the influence of the Atlantic currents, and the colder surface temperatures of the North Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Rainfall totals vary widely across Scotland—the western highlands of Scotland are one of the wettest places in the UK with annual rainfall up to 4,577 mm (180.2 in).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In comparison, much of eastern Scotland receives less than 870 mm (34.3 in) annually; lying in the rain shadow of the western uplands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Annual average sunshine totals vary from as little as 711–1140 hours in the Highlands and the north-west up to 1471–1540 hours on the extreme eastern and south-western coasts.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Wind prevails from the south-west, bringing warm, wet and unstable air from the Atlantic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The windiest areas of Scotland are in the north and west, with parts of the Outer Hebrides, Orkney and Shetland experiencing over 30 days with gales per year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Vigorous Atlantic depressions, also known as European windstorms, are a common feature of the autumn and winter in Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Mesolithic hunter-gatherer encampments formed the first known settlements in Scotland around 8500 BCE.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] These were highly mobile boat-using people making tools from bone, stone and antlers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the Neolithic period, around 6,000 years ago, there is evidence of permanent settlements and farming.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Archaeological evidence indicates that the two main sources of food were grain and cow's milk.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] From the beginning of the Bronze Age, about 2000 BCE, arable land spread at the expense of forest.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] From the Iron Age, beginning in the seventh century BCE, there is evidence of hill forts in southern Scotland that are associated with cultivation ridges and terraces.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Souterrains, small underground constructions, may have been for storing perishable agricultural products.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Aerial photography reveals extensive prehistoric field systems that underlie existing boundaries in some Lowland areas, suggesting that the fertile plains were already densely exploited for agriculture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] During the period of Roman occupation there was re-growth of birch, oak and hazel for five centuries, suggesting a decline of population and agriculture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The early Middle Ages were a period of climate deterioration resulting in more land becoming unproductive.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Most farms had to produce a self-sufficient diet of meat, dairy products and cereals, supplemented by hunter-gathering.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Farming was based around a single homestead or a small cluster of three or four homes, each probably containing a nuclear family.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The climate meant that more oats and barley were grown than corn (here meaning wheat) and cattle were the most important domesticated animal.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters allowed cultivation at much greater heights above sea level and made land more productive.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism from the twelfth century and would continue until the eighteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] With the substantial landholders of the yeomen, these heritors were the major landholding orders.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Many young people, both male and female, left home to become domestic and agricultural servants.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The early modern era also saw the impact of the Little Ice Age, of colder and wetter weather, which peaked towards the end of the seventeenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Almost half the years in the second half of the sixteenth century saw local or national scarcity, necessitating the shipping of large quantities of grain from the Baltic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The closing decade of the seventeenth century there was a slump in trade with the Baltic and France and changes in the Scottish cattle trade, followed by four years of failed harvests (1695, 1696 and 1698-9), known as the "seven ill years".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The shortages of the 1690s would be the last of their kind.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The English plough was introduced and foreign grasses, the sowing of rye grass and clover.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Turnips and cabbages were introduced, lands enclosed and marshes drained, lime was put down to combat soil acidity, roads built and woods planted.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The introduction of the potato to Scotland in 1739 provided a crop with a high yield, producing 3 to 5 times more calories per acre than a cereal crop.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Enclosures began to displace the run rig system.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The first result of these changes were the Lowland Clearances.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The botanist John Hope complained about British naturalists who were enthusiastically exploring the landscape of colonial America while "absolutely inattentive to the natural productions of our native country".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] He founded the Society for the Importation of Foreign Seeds and Plants pursuing, as Carl Linnaeus did in Lapland, the adaptation of valuable cash crop plants to the Highlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Agricultural improvement spread north and west, mostly over the period 1760 to 1850 as the Highland Clearances.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Many farming tenants were evicted and offered tenancies in crofting communities, with their former possessions converted into large-scale sheep farms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Crofts were intended to be too small to support the occupants, so forcing them to work in other industries, such as fishing, quarrying or kelping.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the 1840 and 1850s Scotland suffered its last major subsistence crisis, when the potato blight that caused the Great Famine of Ireland reached the Highlands in 1846.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] This gave rise to the second phase of the Highland clearances, when landlords provided assisted passages for their tenants to emigrate in a desperate effort to rid themselves of a redundant population that was dependent on famine relief.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the twentieth century Scottish agriculture became susceptible to the ups and downs of world markets.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] After World War II there was a drive in UK agriculture to greater production until the late 1970s, resulting in intensive farming.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] More areas of marginal land were brought into production.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There was increasing mechanisation of Scottish agriculture and farming became less labour-intensive.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The UK membership of the European Economic Community (later the European Union) in 1972 began a change in orientation for Scottish farming.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Some sectors, particularly hill sheep farming, became viable only with subsidies.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] A dual farm structure emerged, with agriculture divided between large commercial farms and small pluralised and diversified holdings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] At the time of the June 2013 agricultural census the total area of agricultural holdings in Scotland was 5.6 million hectares, equal to 73 per cent of Scotland’s total land area.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Just over half of this was rough grazing, with about a quarter taken up by grass, and about ten per cent used for crops or left fallow.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The remainder was made up of woodland, ponds, yards or other uses.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There was a further 580,000 hectares of common grazing, which if included made the total area 6.2 million hectares, or 79 per cent of Scotland’s total land area.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Because of the persistence of feudalism and the land enclosures of the nineteenth century, the ownership of most land is concentrated in relatively few hands (some 350 people own about half the land).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] As a result, in 2003 the Scottish Parliament passed Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 that empowered tenant farmers and communities to purchase land even if the landlord did not want to sell.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In June 2013, of crops grown in Scotland (excluding grass), cereals accounted for 78 per cent of the land area, with nearly three-quarters of that being barley (340,000 hectares).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Wheat was also significant (87,000 hectares), along with oilseed rape (34,000 hectares), oats (32,000 hectares) and potatoes (29,000 hectares).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Amongst fruit and vegetables, a total of 911 hectares of strawberries were grown, mainly under cover, which was the largest source of income amongst horticulture crops.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The major areas of cereal production were Grampian, Tayside, Borders, Lothian and Fife.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Livestock numbers have been falling in recent years.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The trend began at the turn of the millennium in the case of pigs and sheep and dates to the mid-1970s in the case of cattle.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In June 2013 there were 6.6 million sheep, 1.8 million cattle and 308,000 pigs, the lowest numbers since the 1940 and 1950s.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Poultry numbers have tended to fluctuate over the last 25 years, but were down to 14.2 million in 2013.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] About 13,340 km2 of land in Scotland is forested representing around 15 per cent of the total land area of Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The majority of forests are in public ownership, with forestry policy being controlled by the Forestry Commission.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The biggest plantations and timber resources are to be found in Dumfries and Galloway, Tayside, Argyll and the area governed by Highland Council.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The economic activities generated by forestry in Scotland include planting and harvesting as well as sawmilling, the production of pulp and paper and the manufacture of higher value goods.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Forests, especially those surrounding populated areas in Central Scotland also provide a recreation resource.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Total income from farming (TIFF) has been rising since the turn of the millennium.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] It was estimated at £700 million in 2012, being made up of £2.9 billion in outputs and £570 million in support payments, offset by £2.8 billion in costs.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The initial estimate of TIFF for 2013 was £830 million, an increase largely linked to the improved weather.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] TIFF per annual work unit increased to £31,000, similar to the value in 2011.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The total output of aquaculture was estimated in 2011 at around £434 million per year, including around £412 million for farmed Atlantic salmon, £14.34 million for rainbow trout and £7.7 million for shellfish.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Brown trout, sea trout, halibut and Arctic charr are also farmed in Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Some farm businesses rely on sources of income other than from farming, including contracting work, hosting mobile phone masts, tourism and recreation and financial support from grants and subsidies.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Analysis of the Farm Accounts Survey suggests that, excluding support from grants and subsidies, the average farm made a loss of £16,000 in 2012.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] However, calculations from TIFF suggest that, excluding support, the sector still made a small profit.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Government figures indicate that in 2013 Scottish agriculture employed around 1.5 per cent of the workforce and contributes around 1 per cent of the Scottish economy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the Highlands and Islands, around 10 per cent of the workforce are engaged in agriculture and livestock products contribute around 70 per cent of the output.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The West of Scotland Agricultural College formed in 1899, the East of Scotland Agricultural College in 1901, and the North of Scotland Agricultural College in 1904; these colleges amalgamated to form the Scottish Agricultural College in 1990.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Site-specific nature conservations began in the UK with the creation of the Nature Conservancy in 1948, which later became the Nature Conservancy Council (NCC).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] It moved from a research-based advisory group to become a campaigning body.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The 1949 National Parks and Access to the Countryside Act excluded Scotland, but introduced the concept of Sites of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI), which were to become a key part of managing nature conservation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] A Countryside Commission Scotland (CSS) was established under the Countryside Scotland Act, 1967.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The NCC was broken up in 1991 and in Scotland was merged with CSS to produce Scottish Natural Heritage (SNH), under a UK-wide Joint Nature Conservation Committee.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] SNH has a remit for both land and nature conservation and a responsibility towards sustainability and to the consideration of the needs of the Scottish people.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In Scotland, a right of way is a route over which the public has been able to pass unhindered for at least 20 years.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The route must link two "public places", such as villages, churches or roads.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Unlike in England and Wales there is no obligation on Scottish local authorities to signpost or mark a right of way.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] However, the charity Scotways, formed in 1845 to protect rights of way, records and signs the routes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 gives everyone statutory access rights to most land and inland water in Scotland, to non-motorized traffic, making the existence of rights of way less important in terms of access to land in Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Certain categories of land are excluded from this presumption of open access, such as railway land, airfields and private gardens.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Agricultural activity occurs in most rural locations.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] It is concentrated in the drier east (for crops) and the wetter west (for livestock).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] There are 191,000 farm holdings, which vary widely in size.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Despite skilled farmers, advanced technology, fertile soil and subsidies, farm earnings are relatively low, mainly due to low prices at the farm gate.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Low earnings, high land prices and a shortage of let farmland discourage young people from joining the industry.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The average (median) age of the British farm holder was about 60 in 2016; the UK government has stopped collecting age data for farmers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Recently there have been moves towards organic farming in an attempt to sustain profits, and many farmers supplement their income by diversifying activities away from pure agriculture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Biofuels present new opportunities for farmers against a background of rising fears about fossil fuel prices, energy security, and climate change.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Intensive agriculture in the UK poses a threat to biodiversity and soil health.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The total area of agricultural holdings is about 41.6 million acres (16.8 million hectares), of which about a third are arable and most of the rest is grassland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] During the growing season about 72% of the arable area is cereal crops, and of the cereal crop area, more than 57% is wheat.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] There are about 33 million sheep, 9.6 million cattle, 188 million poultry and 5.2 million pigs.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] These are arranged on about 191,000 holdings, whose average croppable area is around 69 hectares (170 acres).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] About 70% of farms are owner-occupied or mostly so (perhaps with individual barns or fields let out), and the remainder are rented to tenant farmers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Farmers represent an ageing population, partly due to low earnings and barriers to entry, and it is increasingly hard to recruit young people into farming.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The average farm holder is about 60 years old.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] British farming is on the whole intensive and highly mechanised.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This approach is well-suited to the current distribution infrastructure, but can be less productive by area than smaller scale, diversified farming.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The UK produces only 60% of the food it consumes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The vast majority of imports and exports are with other Western European countries.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Farming is subsidised, with subsidies to farmers totalling more than £3 billion (after deduction of levies).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] While there is little difference between farming practices in England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland in places where the terrain is similar, the geography and the quality of the farmland does have an impact.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In Wales, 80% of the farmland is designated as a "Less Favoured Area", and in Scotland the figure is 84%.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] "Less Favoured Area" means land that produces a lower agricultural yield—typically upland moors and hill farms—which tend to focus on sheep and sometimes dairy farming.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In England, the eastern and southern areas where the fields are flatter, larger and more open tend to concentrate on cereal crops, while the hillier northern and western areas with smaller, more enclosed fields tend to concentrate on livestock farming.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Farming was introduced in the British Isles between about 5000 BC and 4500 BC in an influx of Mesolithic people after the end of the Pleistocene.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] It took 2,000 years for farming to extend across all the isles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Wheat and barley were grown in small plots near family homes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Sheep, goats and cattle came in from Europe, and pigs were tamed from native wild boar.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Agricultural and hunter-gatherer groups met and traded with each other in the early Neolithic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Saxons and the Vikings had open-field farming systems.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Arable farming expanded between the 8th and 13th centuries in England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Under the Normans and Plantagenets fens were drained, woods cleared and farmland expanded to feed a rising population, until the Black Death reached Britain in 1349.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This and later epidemics caused the population to fall; a third of the population in England died between 1349 and 1350.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In consequence, areas of farmland were abandoned.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The feudal system began to break down as labourers, in short supply after the plague, demanded wages (instead of subsistence) and better conditions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Also, a series of poor harvests after about 1315 coincided with poor weather across northern Europe, which continued on and off until about 1375.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The population did not recover to 1300 levels for 200 to 300 years.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The last surviving working mediaeval strip farming system with common grazings is in Laxton, Nottinghamshire in England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] When King Henry VIII made himself Supreme Head of the Church of England in 1531, he set about the dissolution of the monasteries, which was largely complete by 1540.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The monasteries had been major landowners and the Crown took over their land, amounting to about 2,000,000 acres (810,000 ha).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This land was largely sold off to fund Henry's military ambitions in France and Scotland, and the main buyers were the landed gentry.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Agriculture boomed as grain prices increased sixfold by 1650.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Improvements in transport, particularly along rivers and coasts, brought beef and dairy products from the north of England to London.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Jethro Tull, a Berkshire farmer, invented his famous rotating-cylinder seed drill.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] His 1731 book, *The New Horse Hoeing Husbandry*, explained the systems and devices he espoused to improve agriculture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The book had such an impact that its influence can still be seen in some aspects of modern farming.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Charles Townsend, a viscount known as "Turnip Townsend", in the 1730s introduced turnip farming on a large scale.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This created a four-crop rotation (wheat, turnips, barley and clover) which allowed fertility to be maintained with much less fallow land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Clover increases mineral nitrogen in the soil and clover and turnips are good fodder crops for livestock, which in turn improve the soil by their manure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Between 1750 and 1850, the English population nearly tripled, with an estimated increase from 5.7 million to 16.6 million.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] These people were fed by intensified agriculture and land reclamation from the Fens, woodlands, and upland pastures.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The crop mix changed, with wheat and rye replacing barley.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Nitrogen fixing plants such as legumes led to sustainable increased yields.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] These increased yields, combined with improved farming machinery and then-new capitalist ways of organising labour, meant that increased crop production did not need much more manpower, which freed labour for non-agricultural work.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Indeed, by 1850 Britain had the smallest proportion of its population engaged in farming of any country in the world, at 22%.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] During the 18th century, a large share of farmers were literate and numerate, skills that were not widespread in the early modern period.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Open fields divided among several tenants reduced risk by giving all farmers diverse soils and crops, so no one faced famine while others prospered.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Poor farmers got as much land as good farmers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] By the 18th century, enclosures came in poorer regions where several landholders were more willing to sell land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] After 1760, though, new laws allowed the enclosure of lands with more complex ownership structures.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The result was an added £4 million to England's national income.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] During the 18th and 19th centuries, enclosures were by means of special acts of Parliament.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Strips in the open fields became more cohesive units, and remaining pasture commons or *wastes* were enclosed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Enclosure involved extinguishing of common rights.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This allowed farmers to consolidate and fence off their own large plots of land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Voluntary enclosure was also commonplace.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] At the time of the parliamentary enclosures, most manors had seen consolidation of tenant farms into large landholdings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Larger landholders already held the bulk of the land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Although they 'held' land, they did not legally own it in today's sense.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] They also had to respect the open field system rights, when demanded, even when in practice the rights were not widely in use.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Each large landholding would consist of scattered patches, not consolidated farms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In many cases enclosures were largely an exchange and consolidation of land, and exchange not otherwise possible under the legal system.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Enclosure under the scheme of the Inclosure Act 1773 permitted the fencing and regulation of arable land if three quarters of the owners in number and value of the land approved.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Regulations and allotments made were valid for six years.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The lord of the manor and three quarters of the commoners acting together were empowered to lease one twelfth of the land for the improvement of the remainder.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Enclosure following private or local act of Parliament could also extinguish common rights.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Without unanimous extinguishment, the entire system survived at common law.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] With land one held, one could not formally exchange the land, consolidate fields, or entirely exclude others.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Strict enforcement of legal rights may not always have been seen in practice.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Parliamentary inclosure was seen as a cost-effective method of creating a legally binding settlement.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This is because of the costs (time, money, complexity) of using the common law and equity legal systems.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Statute required consent of the owners of 4⁄5ths of the land (copy and freeholders).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The primary benefits to large land holders came from increased value of their own land, not from expropriation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Smaller holders could sell their land to larger ones for a higher price post enclosure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] There was not much evidence that the common rights were particularly valuable.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Protests against parliamentary inclosure continued, sometimes in Parliament itself, frequently in the villages affected, and sometimes as organised mass revolts.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Voluntary enclosure was frequent at that time.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Enclosed land was twice as valuable, a price which could be sustained only by its higher productivity.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Enclosure in Scotland is associated with sudden and large-scale clearances, perhaps due to the prevalence of cottar tenure whereby a dwelling and a small area of land is made available for so long only as the owner of it allows.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The period 1750–1850 included a twenty-year depression in agriculture 1815 to 1836.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] It was so severe that landlords as well as tenants suffered financial ruin, and large areas of farmland were entirely abandoned.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The ancient landlord and tenant system was unsuited to new-style, capital-intensive farms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Parliament began to review the legislation, for example by distinguishing between farm improvements that the tenant should fund, and those the landlord should fund.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Parliament was concerned with the issue of tenant right, i.e. the sum payable to an outgoing tenant for farm improvements that the tenant had funded and, if crops were in the ground when the tenant left, compensation for their value.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This was dealt with in accordance with local custom, which might vary from place to place.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In 1848 a parliamentary committee examined the possibility of a standardised system, but a Bill on the matter was not passed until 1875.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Between 1815 and 1846, Corn Laws were enacted to protect domestic agriculture by imposing a tax on imported grain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] They were repealed after political lobbying by the Anti-Corn Law League.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The issue was divisive because of urbanisation in the UK and its need for cheap food, as well as the influence of free trade doctrines.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Corn Laws' repeal initially steadied grain prices.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Experts differ over whether the Corn Laws were still relevant by 1846, because of low prices and/or self-sufficiency in grain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The American Civil War ended in 1865, and by 1875, with new steam-powered railways and ships, the United States was exporting a substantial excess of cereals.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] At the same time, Britain suffered a series of poor harvests.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] By 1891 reliable refrigeration technology brought cheap frozen meat from Australia, New Zealand and South America to the British market.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] British farm products declined significantly as a percentage of GDP during the period 1860–1914.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In 1860 agriculture represented 20% of GDP.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The period 1850–1914 has been described as "completing the shift to a fundamentally urban and industrial society".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Invented in around 1885, the digging plough is a plough with a wider share, which cuts a wider shallower furrow, after which the slice of soil is inverted by a short concave mould-board with a sharp turn.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This has the effect of breaking up and pulverising the soil, leaving no visible furrow and facilitating the use of a seed drill for planting.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Earlier ploughs were simply large hoes for stirring the soil, drawn by animals, that left furrows suitable for distribution of seed by hand.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The biggest challenge faced by agriculture was the unavailability of manpower due to the large numbers of men who joined the armed forces in the early years of the War.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] By the end of 1916, 4 million men had become participant in the armed forces, and agriculture was given no special treatment.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] It was not until 1917 that agricultural production was overseen by County Executive Committees.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Although rationing during the First World War was limited to the end of 1917 and 1918, a change of mood arose about food security.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Ministry of Food was created in 1916.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] There was an opinion that a man who had fought for his country should be entitled to retire to a smallholding on British land that would provide him with a livelihood.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This led to various initiatives, including making housing available, collectively called "Homes for Heroes." The priorities were established in the Housing, Town Planning, &c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Riddrie, a suburb of Glasgow, was the first estate to be completed in 1922 under that act.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] By 1926 agricultural law had become openly redistributive in favour of ex-servicemen.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] County councils had compulsory purchase powers to requisition land they could let as smallholdings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Ex-servicemen were the preferred tenants.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The tenant could then buy the land and could ask the council to lend them money to fund the purchase as a mortgage.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The council could not refuse without the Minister of Agriculture's permission.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Government control of agriculture during the First World War was removed in 1921 by the repeal of the Agriculture Act 1920.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This has been described as "the great betrayal" but has also been found to be welcomed by a section of the farming community that preferred to trade in the market and resented the previous restraints.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In the inter-war years 1919–1939 agriculture in Britain was not the subject of protectionist policies but had to absorb price falls resulting from increased domestic production and the effects of the imperial preference system favouring the Dominions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] By 1938, 88% of wheat was imported, 96% of butter, 76% of cheese and about half the eggs and meat.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Agricultural Holdings (England) Act 1875 (38 & 39 Vict. c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] 92) rewrote the law on tenant right such that tenants received consistent levels of compensation for the value of their improvements to the holding and any crops in the ground.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] It also gave tenants the right to remove fixtures they had provided, increased the period of a notice to quit from six months to twelve, and brought in an agricultural dispute resolution procedure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Some landlords reacted to the Agricultural Holdings (England) Act 1875 by refusing to let land on a tenancy, instead contracting out the labour to contract farmers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Parliament responded with the Agricultural Holdings (England) Act 1883 (46 & 47 Vict. c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] 61), which prevented contracting out on terms less favourable than a normal tenancy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Subsequently the Agricultural Holdings Act 1900 (63 & 64 Vict. c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] 50) and the Agricultural Holdings Act 1906 (6 Edw.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The legislation was consolidated in the Agricultural Holdings Act 1908 (8 Edw.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Further Agricultural Holdings Acts came into force; the Agricultural Holdings Act 1914 (4 & 5 Geo.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] 76), and then a further consolidating act, the Agricultural Holdings Act 1923 (13 & 14 Geo.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The legislative focus on tenant's improvements is against a background where it was the assumed practice for the tenant to provide seed, implements, livestock, machinery and fertilisers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] By 1914 a large mixed arable/livestock farm would be typically providing £10 per acre of his own capital.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Before the Second World War started, Britain imported 55 million tons of food a year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] By the end of 1939, this had dropped to 12 million.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Grain output rose somewhat during the three years from 1938/1939.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Wheat and barley figures increased by two thirds and potatoes doubled.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Livestock production was static or fell.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Cattle were static and sheep numbers dropped.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Large increases in farm income were effected by direct payments (after the War becoming deficiency payments covering the gap between average farm prices and levels guaranteed for 11 products).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Farm incomes in this three year period accordingly tripled.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Food rationing was introduced at the start of 1940.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] It did not completely end until July 1954.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The government encouraged people to grow their own food in victory gardens, and householders were encouraged to keep rabbits and chickens for the table.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] There were 1.5 million allotments by 1943.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Because so many men had been conscripted into the army, women were drafted in to work the land; they were called the Women's Land Army, or less formally, "land girls".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Famously, the government responded to a temporary wartime oversupply of carrots by suggesting that the RAF's exceptional night-flying was due to eating carotene.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The ruse worked: consumption of carrots increased sharply because people thought carrots might help them see in the blackout, thus taking the pressure off other food supplies.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] But with so much of the agricultural labour force fighting, pressure on food supplies worldwide increased throughout the war.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The government estimated that in 1945 world meat consumption would exceed supply by 1.8 million tons and that only wheat would be "available in abundance".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Prime Minister suggested that if necessary, food supplies could take priority over supplies for the military, and considered the possibility of famine in the occupied territories after the war.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] It was a reaction to the privations of the Second World War, and was aimed at food security, so as to reduce the risk of a hostile foreign power being able to starve the UK into submission.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The act guaranteed prices, markets and tenure, so that a farmer could be assured that his land would not be taken away and whatever he grew would be sold at a known price.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Agricultural Holdings Act 1948 (11 & 12 Geo.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] 63) remained the governing code in England and Wales until its replacement by the Agricultural Holdings Act 1986 (c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] 5), which consolidated intervening amending statutes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] These acts made it hard to evict tenant farmers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] With the new security tenants enjoyed, a system of rent reviews was necessary to take account of land price inflation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] There were many other changes in the law, and each of these acts needed negotiation between the Ministry of Agriculture and the National Farmers Union (NFU) to fix the support price to be paid for each agricultural product.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] They were enacted in a series of acts: the **Agriculture (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1943** (6 & 7 Geo.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] 16), the **Agriculture (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1954** (2 & 3 Eliz.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] 39), the **Agriculture (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1963** (c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] 11), the **Agriculture (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1968** (c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] 34) and the **Agriculture (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1972** (c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The **Agriculture (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1976** (c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] 55) was passed as the price of Plaid Cymru's support in Parliament for the Lib-Lab Pact of 1976.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The 1976 act allowed for succession of agricultural tenancies on a farmer's death.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] A suitable relative could inherit the tenancy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This was limited to two generations of tenant.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] On government instructions, the Northfield Committee began to review the country's agricultural system in 1977.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The report influenced ongoing discussions between the NFU and the Country Landowners Association (CLA), who were trying to reach an agreement on legislation that could be presented as having industry-wide support.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In 1984, in accordance with the agreement they did reach, succession was extended to the retirement of the tenant, but no new tenancies from 1984 were to include succession rights.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] By this time the then-European Economic Community (EEC, now the European Community)'s Common Agricultural Policy and the value of the green pound was having a direct impact on farming.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] 49) was concerned with the value of the milk quota attached to land, and particularly how it ought to be shared between landlord and tenant.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Nowadays, milk quotas no longer exist, but other subsidies (largely rolled up into 'single payments') still must be divided between the parties.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The UK's egg-laying flock declined between 1970 and 2000.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] It fell by 5.5% in one year from June 1999 to May 2000.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In 1971, there were 125,258 farms with egg-laying hens and by 1999 this was down to 26,500.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] From 1992 until 2004, or 2006 for organic farms, there were subsidies for not growing any crops at all.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This was called set-aside and resulted from EEC farming policies.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] From 2007 onwards, set aside subsidies in the UK were withdrawn.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Winter crops tend to be planted around mid-September, and spring crops as soon as the soil is ready.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Each year the country produces about 6.5 million tonnes of barley, of which 1.5 million are exported, 2 million used in brewing and distilling activities and the remainder fed to livestock.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The country also produces 14 to 15 million tons of wheat each year, of which farmers kept 3.9 million tonnes as stock in February 2012.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Most farmers of beef cattle or sheep made a net loss in the year to April 2010.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Production, veterinary, bedding, property, power and machinery costs all underwent double-digit rises in percentage terms, meaning that the losses in the year to April 2010 increased over 2009 losses by over £30/animal.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] However, wheat exports were much stronger than the previous year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In 2011, earnings were £30,900 per full-time person, which represented an increase of 24% from 2010 values in real terms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This was the best performance in UK agriculture since the 1990s.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Agriculture employed 476,000 people, representing 1.5% of the workforce, down more than 32% since 1996.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In terms of gross value added in 2009, 83% of the UK's agricultural income originated from England, 9% from Scotland, 4% from Northern Ireland and 3% from Wales.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In 2014, total income from farming in the United Kingdom was £5.38 billion, representing about 0.7% of the British national value added in that year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] From 2002 to 2003, of the cereals grown, 31% of barley, 36% of oats and 34% of wheat were used for human consumption.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Consumption of oats by the human population compared with livestock was proportionally higher in the UK than in European countries, 455,000 tonnes as forecast by farm officials during 2012.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Two of the most serious diseases affecting crop plants were colony collapse disorder (CCD), wiping out honeybee colonies worldwide, and *varroa destructor*, a parasitic mite affecting honeybees.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Honeybees pollinated 80% of plants worldwide.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In 2007, up to 80% of the bee colonies in some areas were wiped out.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Honeybees pollinated crops worth about £200 million a year, and their total contribution to the economy might have been as high as £1 billion.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Board of Agriculture was established by the Board of Agriculture Act 1889 (52 & 53 Vict. c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Board of Agriculture for Scotland was created under the Secretary of State for Scotland by the Small Landholders (Scotland) Act 1911 (1 & 2 Geo.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In England and Wales, the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries Act 1919 (9 & 10 Geo.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] 91) replaced the Board of Agriculture and Fisheries by the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries, which later became the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (MAFF).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] MAFF was the predecessor of the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, DEFRA.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Scotland's agriculture is controlled by the Scottish Government and its Agriculture and Rural Economy Directorate.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Welsh government also controls agriculture as a devolved matter under the aegis of the Minister for Rural Affairs.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Northern Irish agriculture is within the control of the Department of Agriculture, Environment and Rural Affairs (DAERA) which is part of the Northern Ireland Executive.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Environment, Food and Rural Affairs Committee (EFRA) of the Westminster Parliament's House of Commons is tasked to oversee and enquire into the policy, administration and spending of DEFRA.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] It conducts its own inquiries usually leading to published Reports.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] EFRA may also inquire into matters that do not lead to formal reports, and it is empowered to conduct interviews and take evidence.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Economy, Trade, and Rural Affairs Committee of the Welsh Parliament supervises the Welsh Government in respect of animal welfare, environment, agriculture, forestry, food, marine resources and fisheries as well as trade and economy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The supervising bodies of the Scottish Parliament include the Rural Economy and Connectivity Committee with oversight of agriculture and forestry, and the Rural Affairs and Islands Committee responsible for land use, food, animal welfare and fisheries.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Committee for Agriculture, Environment and Rural Affairs of the Northern Ireland Assembly is tasked to advise and assist the DAERA Minister and operates in accordance with its mandate periods.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] When in the EU, UK farmers received more than £3 billion a year via the Single Farm Payment.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This is roughly £28,300 per farm, although this includes around £3,000 of environmental subsidies, such as for planting woodland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Following Brexit a new subsidy scheme is being introduced with a proposed reduction in direct payments with an increase in payments tied to specific environmental or developmental criteria.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] DEFRA's *Agri-climate Report 2022* states that agriculture is a major contributor to UK nitrous oxide (69%) and methane (48%) emissions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] It contributes 1.7% to UK CO2 emissions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Levels have been steady since the early 2000s when a 16% drop was achieved from the 1990s.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] A study of farmer awareness of mitigation measures indicates that barriers to mitigation practices include lack of information, the belief change is not necessary and financial barriers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Utilised Agricultural Area (UAA), as of 2022, was 41.619 million acres (16.843 million hectares), approximately 69% of the land area of the UK.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The UAA encompasses land used for agricultural purposes, including all arable and horticultural crops, uncropped arable land, common rough grazing, temporary and permanent grassland and land used for outdoor pigs.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] It excludes woodland and other non-agricultural land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Approximately 36% of the land is croppable (arable), or approximately 25% of the total UK land area.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Most of the rest is permanent grassland, rough grazing and other land on agricultural holdings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Land classification maps were issued first in the 1960s, intended as a tool for the better siting of planned new towns.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] They were provisional in contents but in fact were not updated.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Areas of under 80 hectares were stated not to be identifiable from these maps, which were reissued in the 1980s at a different scale (1:250,000 or one quarter inch to the mile).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The British Society of Soil Science has published a guide to the history and mapping of UK land classifications.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Land is classified in England and Wales in accordance with five grades.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] These grades are established using information as to soil quality and characteristics together with climatological data.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The planning system requires permission for many kinds of development.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Superior grades of agricultural land, meaning grades 1-3a inclusive, are less likely to be permitted to be developed and so fall out of agricultural use.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] These superior grades of land are the subject of a separate set of maps (Likelihood of Best and Most Versatile (BMV) Agricultural Land - Strategic scale maps) for strategic planning purposes only for the English regions, also available online from Natural England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Sale or letting of land may use the land classification to price the land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Setting rents or evaluating dilapidations (disrepair or breach of obligation on tenanted farms) will probably include reference to this information.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Land restoration projects for contaminated land will use such information.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Road surveys for building or extending highways will require to include land classification information.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Agricultural Land Classification maps are available by online download for England and Wales from Natural England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The English regions have individual maps for: London and the South East; the Eastern Region; the East Midlands; the West Midlands; Yorkshire and Humber; the North East; the North West; the South West.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Revised criteria for land grading dated 1988 are provided at the same site, together with climatological data used for the purpose of mapping, and soil sample data with a glossary.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Welsh government, in applying the same grading system, offers predictive map guidance online so that it is easier to decide whether an individual land survey is required to establish the grading of the land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] For Wales, the Land Quality Advice Service is the responsible agency.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Scotland uses its own classification system for Land Capability for Agriculture (LCA).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Prime Quality Land is in Classes 1–3.1 inclusive, corresponding to the superior grades 1–3a in the English/Welsh system.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Downloadable data and maps are available from the Scottish Government online.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Scottish planning policy may require superior grades of land and peatland to be identified.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] There are no Agricultural Land Classification maps, but the system reflects the same grading and criteria as for England and Wales.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Grade 3 is designated into 3A and 3B (capitalisation deliberate).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Agri-Food and Business Sciences Institute (AFBI) has created publications with data specific to Northern Ireland in the form of soil surveys, geo-chemical data and soil maps.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Soil is a mix of mineral and organic components, produced when rock is weathered and acted on by living organisms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] If soils are acidic they may need repeated applications of alkalines (such as lime) to remain fertile.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Acid rain increases soil acidity, but even normal rain may be slightly acid.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In freely-drained areas, soil base material (including dissolved nitrites) may be washed away, leaving higher concentrations of organic acids in the ground.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Wet soil results where rainfall exceeds the rate of evaporation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Most British soils are 2% to 5% organic and 95% to 98% mineral, but soils such as peat may contain up to 50% organic matter.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] As far south as the Thames Valley, the soil has been heavily glaciated, which ground down the rock and redistributed the resulting matter.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Most British soils date from the last Ice Age and are comparatively young, but in level areas, and particularly south of the Thames Valley, there are older soils.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Aside from the information above under Agricultural Land Classification, DEFRA has published a *Soil Code*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] There is also a *Construction Code of Practice for the Sustainable Use of Soils on Construction Sites*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The latter was under review as at August 2022.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Guidance is also available in DEFRA's *Good Practice for Handling Soils* (2000) and its *Guidance for Successful Reclamation of Mineral and Waste Sites* (2005).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Owing to high rainfall in the UK, less well drained areas may become waterlogged.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Wet land is more difficult to work and crops grow less well.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Field drains were traditionally open ditches, but covered pipes have been used in more modern times.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Earthworms are important for creating small drainage channels in the soil and for helping to move soil particles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] With fine particulate soils such as clays, lime also encourages the formation of a better soil structure that will aerate and help with drainage.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Its benefits have been known, if not scientifically understood, since Roman times.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] If organic matter poor in nitrogen but rich in carbohydrate is added to soil, nitrogen is assimilated and fixed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Fertility increases while land is under grass, which helps to accumulate organic matter in the soil.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] These factors mean that soil is traditionally improved by means of liming, draining, and allowing to lie fallow.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] It is traditionally fertilised with manure, nitrogen, phosphates, and potash.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Nitrogen stimulates plant growth, but over-application softens the plant tissues, making them more vulnerable to pests and disease, and less resistant to frost.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Nitrogen may be added by using slurry, by nitrogen-fixing crops or by artificial fertilisers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The negative side-effects of adding nitrogen are mitigated by phosphates.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The risk of excess nitrogen polluting water is the focus of designating Nitrate Vulnerable Zones.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] 170 million tonnes of animal excreta ("slurry") is produced annually in the UK.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Farmyard manure can be used as soil fertiliser.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Urine contains about half the nitrogen and most of the potash that an animal voids.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Dung contains the other half of the nitrogen and most of the phosphoric acid and lime.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] With dung, much of the nitrogen is lost in storage or locked up in slowly released forms, so greater quantities are necessary compared to artificial fertilisers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Manure is most effective when ploughed into the fields while it is still fresh, but this is not practical while crops are growing.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In practice, most manure is stored and then applied in winter, or else added in ridges for root crops.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Slurry can pollute watercourses, draining them of oxygen, can contain pathogenic microorganisms such as salmonella, and creates an odour that causes complaints if stored near people.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Pigs and poultry, if kept intensively with a relatively small land area per animal, create manure that requires to be processed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This may be done by removing the liquid component and transporting it away, or by composting it, or by anaerobic digestion to produce methane which is later converted to electricity.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Slurry lagoons that are open are polluting infrastructure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] New grants as of 2022 will pay towards conversion of stores to closed stores with minimum 6 months storage.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Acidification treatment or covers will be required under the scheme.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Many existing stores are concrete or steel structures.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Leguminous plants such as peas, beans or lucerne live in a symbiotic relationship with certain bacteria that produce nodules on their roots.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The bacteria extract nitrogen from the air and convert it to nitrogenating compounds that benefit the legume.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] When the legume dies or is harvested, its rotting roots add nitrogen compounds to the soil.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Where nitrogen from soil gets into the water, it can be hazardous to human health.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] EC Directive 80/778/EEC and 91/676/EEC both state a ceiling acceptable level of nitrates of 50 mg/litre, which is also the level recommended by the World Health Organization.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] In several places in Britain, particularly in the Midlands and the South East, nitrate concentrations occasionally exceed this level and the government has brought in regulations to control nitrate levels in the water.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The regulations governing designated Nitrate Vulnerable Zones (NVZ) aim to protect ground and surface water from contamination with nitrates and manure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Around 68% of English farmland, 14% of Scottish farmland and all of Welsh farmland is within a NVZ.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The NVZ rules control at what time of year farmers may apply nitrogen or manure to the land and oblige them to keep strict records of nitrogen-containing substances used.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] They also regulate slurry and manure storage.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The Welsh Government introduced an all Wales NVZ in 2021.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Previously, 2.4% of Wales' land was designated as a NVZ.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Environmental and fishing groups welcomed the new rules.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] It will be rolled out, pending a review by the Senedd, over the next three years.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] The review came after major political backlash from opposition parties and farmers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Phosphates are substances that contain phosphorus, which stimulates root development in young plants.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] It also increases yields and speeds up plant growth.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Phosphates are not easily lost from soil, but mostly occur in stable forms that are not liberated quickly enough by natural processes, so fertilisation is necessary.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Traditionally, phosphate-bearing materials added to soil include bonemeal, powdered slag, and seaweed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Potash is a substance that contains potassium.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] This promotes disease resistance and helps to build starches and sugars.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Plants tend to absorb potash during early stages of growth, and potash may reduce problems caused by applying nitrogen.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Potash also increases the weight of an individual cereal grain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Traditional potash sources included applying ash to the land and ploughing in crop residues after the harvest.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Artificial potash fertilisers were not used until deposits of potash salts were discovered in Germany in 1861.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Arable farming is the production of crops.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Crop growth is affected by light, soil, nutrients, water, air, and climate.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Crops commonly grown in the United Kingdom include cereals, chiefly wheat, oats and barley; root vegetables, chiefly potatoes and sugar beet; pulse crops such as beans or peas; forage crops such as cabbages, vetches, rape and kale; fruit, particularly apples and pears; and hay for animal feed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Seeds may be sown in spring, summer or autumn.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Spring-sown crops are vulnerable to drought in May or June.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Autumn sowing is usually restricted to frost-hardy types of bean, vetch, or cereal such as winter wheat.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Traditional sowing techniques include broadcasting, dibbling, drilling, and ploughing in.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Drilling is normally the most economical technique where conditions are dry enough.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Climate change will have positive impacts on crop production in Ireland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The combined effects of higher CO 2 concentration, warmer spring/summer temperatures and lengthened growing season will all be beneficial to certain types of crop production, specifically grains and barley and detrimental to other crops, such as potatoes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Ploughing is not always regarded as essential nowadays, but the plough can improve soil by inverting it to improve soil aeration and drainage, release nutrients through weathering, and expose harmful pests to predators.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It is also an effective method of weed control.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Ploughing depth in Britain varies between 5–6 inches in some limestone regions to up to 18 inches in deep stoneless silt land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Most British ploughs are designed to turn a furrow of up to about a foot deep, which is relatively shallow compared to some other countries, where furrows of up to 16 inches are common.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Reaping is the process of harvesting a crop.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Traditionally reaping was done with the scythe and reaping hook, but in Britain these have been entirely superseded by machinery.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Combine harvesters, so called because they both harvest and thresh the crop, are common.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Other machines used include mowers, reapers, binders, harvesters, pea cutters and flax pullers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Once reaped, some crops are brought directly to market.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Others need to be threshed to separate the cash crop from the straw and chaff.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Wheat, oats, barley, beans and some kinds of small seed (e.g. clover) typically need to be threshed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Since the Second World War, scientific and technical progress and the removal of tenancy-based restrictions on choice of crop have given British arable farmers a great deal more freedom to plan cropping sequences.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Strict crop rotation is no longer technically necessary or even financially desirable.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Factors that influence crop sequences include the soil type, weather, the price and availability of labour and power, market outlets, and technical considerations about maintaining soil fertility and crop health.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] For example, some vigorous crops such as kale or arable silage will, when liberally fertilised, tend to outgrow and smother weeds.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Many pests and diseases are crop-specific and the more often a particular crop is taken, the greater the buildup of pests and diseases that attack it.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The farmer will therefore try to design a sequence to sustain high yields, permit adequate weed control, service market needs, and keep the soil free from diseases and pests.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] As a direct result of climate change, harvesting is coming earlier in the year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The increased temperatures and CO 2 levels allow this to happen.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] This means crops can be harvested well in advance of the heavy rain season.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Most diseases of crop plants result from fungus spores that may live in the soil and enter through roots, be airborne and enter the plant through damaged areas or landing on leaf surfaces, or are spread by pests.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] These spores tend to affect photosynthesis and reduce chlorophyll.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] They often make plants look yellow and affect growth and marketability of the crop.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] They are most commonly treated with fungicides, and may be called mildews, rusts, blotches, scabs, wilts, rots or blights.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] European Union regulations on pesticides are changing, and several important pesticides currently in use will no longer be available.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] This has potentially quite serious implications for British agriculture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Climate change is bringing with it the earlier onset of winter rain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] These very wet soils during spring time will also lead to unwanted pest and disease problems during the plating season.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Historically weed control was by hand-pulling of weeds, often during "fallowing" (which means leaving the land to carry no crop for a season, during which time the weeds can be found and removed).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In 1896 it was found that a copper sulphate solution would kill broad-leaved weeds without seriously damaging young cereal plants.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Other chemical weedkillers were soon discovered and now common chemical weedkiller ingredients include sodium chlorate, copper chloride, sulphuric acid, dinitroorthocresol and dinitrobutylphenol.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Hormone-based weedkillers are used to kill weeds more selectively.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Although most weeds are vulnerable to at least one of these substances, eradicating all the weeds from a particular area will usually need several different weedkillers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The use of pesticides has declined, and British farmers now use about a third less pesticides than they did in 1983.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The crop needing most pesticides is wheat.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In Scotland there is a code of practice, the *Pesticides: code of practice for using plant protection products in Scotland* (2007).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] A pest is an animal that eats or spoils food meant for humans.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Pests damage crops by removing leaf area, severing roots, or simply gross damage.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In the UK, they are invertebrates (chiefly nematodes, slugs and insects or insect larvae), mammals (particularly rabbits) and birds (mainly members of the pigeon family).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The damage caused by crop pests is considerable.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] For example, potato cyst nematodes cause over £50 million damage a year in the UK.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Secretary of State for DEFRA can, under section 98 of the Agriculture Act 1947, intervene to compel or assist with pest control by destruction of animals, birds and eggs specified in a notice.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Such animal pests are defined as "rabbits, hares and other rodents, deer, foxes and moles".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Birds are defined for these purposes as wild birds other than those included in the first schedule to the Protection of Birds Act 1954.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Secretary of State may assist in the process of pest extermination by providing equipment or services and recoup the reasonable cost of doing so.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Actions prohibited by the Game Act 1831 (1 & 2 Will.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] 32) are not authorised by a notice under the Agriculture Act 1947.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] As of 2026 the Game Act 1831 remains in force.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It prohibits, amongst other things, taking game at certain times and also the laying down of poison for game.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Pastoral farming is the breeding of livestock for meat, wool, eggs and milk, and historically (in the UK) for labour.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Livestock products are the main element of the UK's agricultural output.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The most common meat animals in the United Kingdom are cattle, pigs, sheep and poultry.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Overwhelmingly, British wool comes from sheep, with only a few goats or alpacas bred for exotic wools such as cashmere or angora.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The vast majority of milk comes from cattle, and eggs from chickens.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Nevertheless, because dairy cattle must calve to produce milk, much of the British beef output is from surplus dairy herd calves.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] There are about 17,000 dairy farms in the UK, largely in the west.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Average herd size is 86 cows in England, 75 in Wales and 102 in Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Most cows are milked twice a day, and an average dairy cow yields 6,300 litres a year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The most important dairy cattle breed is the ubiquitous British Friesian, which has largely replaced the Dairy Shorthorn in British dairy herds thanks both to its high milk yield and the relatively high quality of the beef it produces.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The UK once produced roughly as much beef as it ate, but this changed in 1996 because of bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The BSE crisis led to regulations preventing animals more than 30 months old from entering the food chain, which meant cull cows could no longer be sold for beef.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Just under 6 million cattle over this age were destroyed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] A Calf Purchase Aid Scheme, under which a further nearly 2 million calves were slaughtered, ended in 1999.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In 2002, the UK produced 72% of the beef it ate.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Important beef cattle breeds include the Hereford, which is the most popular British beef breed, and the Aberdeen Angus.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The once-widespread Beef Shorthorn is now a relatively uncommon sight.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Cows require significant areas of grassland to raise.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Dairy cows need 0.4 to 0.5 hectares per cow, including the area needed for winter silage; suckler beef cows can need up to a whole hectare each.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] UK animal welfare law requires that animals are kept in daylight in groups with bedding and access to hay, silage or straw.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] This produces "pink" veal where the calves grow more slowly.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It was initially less desirable to some continental customers than the "white" veal produced in harsher conditions for the calf.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Over 41,000 farms in the UK produce sheep, but more than half of breeding ewes are on hill or upland farms suitable for little else.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] National Parks and heather moors such as the Lake District, the Pennines and Snowdonia in Wales are dominated by sheep farms, as are the Scottish Highlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In the lowlands, pockets of sheep farms remain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Romney Marsh (which gave its name to the Romney sheep) and The Downs in Kent are famous for their sheep.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Sheep farming in Wales encompasses both upland and lowland areas.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The number of sheep farmed in the UK peaked in 1998 at 20.3 million, as a result of the Sheepmeat Regime, a relatively generous EU support initiative first begun in 1980.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Numbers declined following the 2001 outbreak of foot and mouth, and the UK temporarily lost its place as Europe's largest producer of lamb, although this was recovered later.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Nowadays many ewes are housed indoors for lambing, which costs more but facilitates earlier lambing with lower mortality and replacement rates.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It also rests and protects the grassland, leading to better early growth and higher stocking rates.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Sheep are also important in helping to manage the landscape.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Their trampling hinders bracken spread and prevents heather moor from reverting to scrub woodland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Wool production is no longer economically important in the UK, and nowadays, sheared fleeces are often treated as a waste product.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Pig farming is concentrated in Yorkshire and East Anglia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] About 4,600 farms produce pigs, and the UK is 90% self-sufficient in pork, but only about 40% self-sufficient in bacon and ham, which reflects a traditional British preference for these cuts.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Nowadays many pig farms in the UK breed intensively farmed hybrids of types like the Large White, British Landrace, Welsh or British Saddleback, and formerly popular breeds like the Cumberland and Small White are extinct.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] They are currently covered under the Dangerous Wild Animals Act 1976 and farmers need permission from their local authority to keep them.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The UK pig herd is declining, and there are now some individual pig farms in the US that have more sows than there are in the UK as a whole.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Pigs often used to be kept indoors throughout their lives, but welfare concerns and increased costs have led to more outdoor units, and by 2002 30% of sows were outdoors.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In many countries sows are kept tethered in individual stalls, but this system was banned in the UK in 1999 on animal welfare grounds.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Each sow produces an average of 24 piglets a year and will be pregnant or lactating for 340 days a year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] This intensive production wears the sows out, and about 40% of them need to be replaced each year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] A major byproduct of pig production is slurry.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] One sow and her piglets can produce ten tonnes of slurry a year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Because regulations limit how much slurry can be loaded onto a given area of land, this means that each sow with her progeny will manure at least 0.8 hectares.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] This is a problem because pig manure is mildly toxic, owing to the use of copper as a growth enhancer.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The UK has about 73,000 goats, mostly as milk producers; this number is relatively small by EU standards.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Venison production in the UK is mainly from red deer, with a few fallow deer as well, but there are only about 300 venison-producing farms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] As noted above, there are about 26,500 farms with chickens.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] However, more than half the UK's eggs come from fewer than 400 flocks, mostly with more than 50,000 birds each.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Other livestock and poultry farmed on a smaller scale include game birds, ducks, geese, turkeys, ostriches and rabbits.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In this way, the UK produce annually 22 million turkeys.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Farmers wanting to move their livestock outside their own farms must obey the Disease Control (England) Order 2003 (SI 2003/1729), the Disease Control (Wales) Order 2003 (SI 2003/1966) or the Disease Control (Interim Measures) (Scotland) Order 2002 (SSI 2002/34), as applicable.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] This means a farmer needs a licence from the local authority to move livestock.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] There are also minimum "standstill" periods once livestock has been moved, so for example, a farmer buying new cattle and moving them onto his farm must then wait six days before taking other cattle to market.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Each individual cow must have a "passport" issued by the British Cattle Movement Service.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Other farm animals such as sheep, goats or pigs must have a herd mark.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Designated notifiable diseases under the Animal Health Act 1981 include anthrax, foot-and-mouth disease, fowl pest, bovine tuberculosis, BSE, scrapie, swine vesicular disease, Aujeszky's disease, bovine leukemia virus, rabies and warble fly.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Under the Zoonoses Order conditions that can be transmitted to humans, such as brucellosis or salmonella, must also be notified.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The United Kingdom suffered outbreaks of foot-and-mouth disease in 1967 and 2001, with a less serious outbreak in 2007.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] There was also an outbreak of bluetongue in 2007.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The most serious disease to affect British agriculture was BSE, a cattle brain disease that causes a similar disease in some humans who eat infected meat.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It has killed 166 people in Britain since 1994.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] A current issue is the control of bovine tuberculosis, which can also be carried by badgers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It is alleged that the badgers are infecting the cows.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] A scientific report for the government recommended a selective cull of badgers, which immediately met with opposition from other scientists.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The government is currently consulting on this issue.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] As of 16 September 2011, a total of 27 online petitions had attracted 65,000 signatures opposing the plan.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Animal welfare legislation affecting UK agriculture includes the Animal Welfare Act 2006, the Welfare of Farmed Animals (England) Regulations 2007 (SI 2007/2078), the Welfare of Farmed Animals (Wales) Regulations 2007 (SI 2007/3070) and the Welfare of Animals (Transport) Order 1997 (SI 1997/1480).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The UK has a good reputation for animal welfare, and there are several codes of practice.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Animal welfare as an issue is increasingly important.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Although welfare-conscious husbandry can have economic benefits to the farmer, because a happy animal puts on weight more rapidly and will reproduce more easily, the mere fact that an animal is gaining weight or reproducing does not necessarily indicate a high level of animal welfare.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Generally there is a tension between the minimum acceptable level of animal welfare for the consumer, the price of the product, and an acceptable margin for the farmer.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] This tension is resolved by food labelling that enables the consumer to choose the price they pay for a given level of animal welfare.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] So for example, many consumers prefer to buy free range eggs even where these are more expensive than eggs from battery hens.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Nowadays, there are various welfare assurance schemes in response to consumer pressure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Royal Agricultural University, which was the first agricultural college in the English-speaking world, opened as the Royal Agricultural College in 1845.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It was granted its royal charter shortly after its founding.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] By the latter half of the nineteenth century, as farming grew more complex and methodical and as productivity increased, there was a dawning recognition that farmers needed agricultural education.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Thanks to government financial support for agricultural education in the 1890s, the Royal Agricultural College was followed by Writtle College in 1893 and Harper Adams University College in 1901.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Meanwhile, the West of Scotland Agricultural College formed in 1899, the East of Scotland Agricultural College in 1901, and the North of Scotland Agricultural College in 1904; these colleges amalgamated to form the Scottish Agricultural College in 1990.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Professor John Wrightson opened his private Downton Agricultural College in 1880; it closed in 1906 as it was unable to compete with the publicly funded state colleges.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In England the Royal Agricultural University in Cirencester offers degree-level education and research opportunities in agriculture, as does Harper Adams University in Shropshire.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Hartpury University is in Gloucestershire.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In Scotland, Scotland's Rural College operates from Aberdeen.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] There is no specialist agricultural university in Wales, though courses in agriculture are available.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] There is also a specialist agricultural college in Northern Ireland, the College of Agriculture, Food and Rural Enterprise (CAFRE).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] There are numerous bodies and associations, charities and others interested in agriculture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Agricultural Law Association (ALA) is a non-political organisation of legal and other experts in agricultural law which offers advice in response to government consultations.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Members may be qualified lawyers, surveyors or otherwise professionally qualified.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Members may also be qualified as Fellows by the ALA.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The ALA operates throughout the UK via regional groups.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Central Association of Agricultural Valuers was founded in 1910 from a number of local associations.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Its current membership is approximately 3,000 who are qualified by the CAAV and are rural agricultural professionals.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The organisation operates throughout the UK and does so via its committee network.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It provides information resources, meetings, and advice in and regarding government consultations.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Country Land and Business Association (CLA), formerly known as the Country Landowners' Association, represents a 28,000 membership base of people or organisations owning land in England and Wales.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Its purpose is to provide membership services and information, as well as lobbying to secure desired policy outcomes for landowner members.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Farmers' Union of Wales was formed in 1955 to represent those members farming in Wales.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It has the right to represent Welsh farmers in UK government consultations.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The National Farmers Union (NFU) was begun by a group of nine Lincolnshire farmers and, as the "Lincolnshire Farmers Union", held its first meeting in 1904.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] By 1908 they were called the National Farmers Union and were meeting in London.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] During the Second World War, the NFU worked closely with the Ministry of Agriculture to ensure food security.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Rationing continued after the war and it is a measure of the NFU's influence at that time that the Agriculture Act 1947 committed the government to undertake a national review of the industry every year in consultation with the NFU.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] After the 2001 creation of DEFRA, the NFU continued to influence policy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The main NFU operates in England and Wales.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Welsh section is known as NFU Cymru.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The farming and horticultural business base of the NFU as at 2023 stood at over 46,000 business members.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The organisation is concerned with promoting the interests of its members by lobbying and campaigning, the provision of information and making available other services to members.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] NFU Scotland was founded in 1913 and as at 2023 represents approximately 10,000 farmers in Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Its purpose is to further the interests of its members and to inform and represent them.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Scottish Crofting Federation operates in Scotland and is concerned to promote and protect crofting, a form of small-scale farming found in the Highlands and Islands of Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Scottish Tenant Farmers' Association, which operates in Scotland, was founded in 2001.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It was originally known as the Tenant Farmers' Action Group.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Its members are tenants of farms in Scotland and its purpose is to inform membership and promote its interests including by legislative change.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Tenant Farmers' Association was formed in 1981 and operates in England and Wales.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Its purpose is to represent tenant farmer members and to lobby on their behalf.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It provides information and some services.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Ulster Farmers' Union was founded in 1918 and operates in Northern Ireland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It has approximately 12,500 members and its purpose is to promote their interests by professional lobbying.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Unite the Union is the biggest trade union for food and farming workers, with Unite's Food, Drink, and Agricultural sector representing over 100,000 members.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It was formed in mid 2015 from a merger of Unite's food, drink and tobacco sector, with Unite's rural and agricultural sector.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The sector inherited its paper, *Landworker*, from the former National Union of Agricultural and Allied Workers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The union nominates six representatives to the Scottish Agricultural Wages Board to represent workers' interests, six to the Agricultural Wages Board for Northern Ireland, and two to the Agricultural Advisory Panel for Wales.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In the 1930s land with vacant possession cost an average of £60 per hectare.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In the same period retail prices rose by a factor of 35, but agricultural land prices rose by a factor of well over 100.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In England and Wales the Agricultural Holdings Act 1986, which consolidated and built on a century-long trend of increasing protection for tenants, became so onerous towards landlords that they were reluctant to let land at all.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It became so hard to obtain a tenancy that the farming industry supported reform ending security of tenure for new tenancies.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Thus the Agricultural Tenancies Act 1995 led to the creation of Farm Business Tenancies.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Since then most new tenancies in England and Wales have been Farm Business Tenancies under the 1995 Act.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] 1986 Act tenancies remain in force and allow succession, by up to two generations of family tenant.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In 2011 the most common route of entry into farming was to succeed to a holding, whether as owner or tenant, so a person's opportunity to farm depended primarily on a family connection.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Biofuels are fuels derived from biomass.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] They can be used in their pure form to power vehicles, but most commonly they are blended with traditional fuels such as diesel.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In 2003, the European Union saw biofuels as an answer to several problems: climate change, energy security and stimulating the rural economy, and agreed the Biofuels Directive to see that production was kickstarted.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In 2008, the Gallagher Review expressed concern about the effects of the biofuels initiative and identified the conversion of agricultural land to biofuels production as a factor in rising food prices.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The current recommended option is that farmers should use marginal or waste land to produce biofuels and maintain production of food on prime agricultural land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation ("RTFO") obliges fuel suppliers to see that a certain proportion of the fuel they sell comes from renewable sources.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] This presents a potentially useful source of revenue for some farmers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Biofuel crops grown in the UK include oilseed rape (which is also grown for other purposes), short-rotation coppices such as poplar or willow, and *miscanthus*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Unfortunately biofuels are quite bulky for their energy yield, which means processing into fuel needs to happen near where the crop is grown; otherwise, most or all of the benefit of biofuels can be lost in transporting the biofuel to the processing area.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Such local processing units are not generally available in the UK, and further expansion of this market will depend on politics and industrial finance.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It was first suggested that farmers could be paid for "producing countryside" in 1969, but the real beginning of positive agri-environmental policy came with the Agriculture Act 1986.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Countryside Stewardship Scheme and local equivalents were run by the Countryside Commission and the Countryside Council for Wales from 1991 until 1996, when they came under ministry control.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Nowadays schemes to encourage farmers to think about wildlife conservation and to farm in an environmentally friendly way abound, though actual payments to farmers to support this are comparatively modest.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] When EU subsidy regime changes in 2013, farmers will receive a greater proportion of their payments from "management of natural resources and climate action".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] This forms one of the three "principal objectives" of the reformed Common Agricultural Policy which is under consultation until March 2012.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] About half of all farmers in the United Kingdom supplement their income by diversifying their businesses away from pure agriculture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] On average diversification adds £10,400 to a farm's revenue.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Sporting rights over farmland for hunting or trapping game have commercial value; game shooting, deer stalking and fishing contribute to the UK economy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Fox hunting has been banned in the United Kingdom since February 2005.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Farmland may, for example, be converted to equestrian facilities, amenity parkland, country clubs, hotels, golf courses, camping and caravan sites.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Farmers open shops, restaurants and even pubs to sell their products.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The large discrepancy is probably because the census data excluded the letting or subletting of buildings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The most common kinds of diversification are probably letting of barns as warehouses and storage, letting of former farm labourers' cottages (whether as holiday cottages or on longer leases) and farm shops.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The number of farm shops in the UK increased by more than 50% between 1999 and 2003.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] There is grant funding available for diversification schemes, as well as other initiatives to improve competitiveness in the farming sector, through the Rural Development Programme for England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The scheme runs until 2013, is managed through Defra and has been delivered to date through Regional Development Agencies.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Expenditure on the Rural Development Programme for England will remain around £3.7 billion for the 2007–13 programme period, compared with the original planned budget of about £3.9 billion.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Organic farming is farming without chemical fertilisers, most pesticides, genetic modification, or the routine use of drugs, antibiotics or wormers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In the United Kingdom it is supported and encouraged by the Soil Association.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Food Standards Agency says that organic food offers no additional nutritional benefits over the non-organic kind, though the Soil Association disputes this.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] However, there are definite benefits in terms of on-farm conservation and wildlife.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In the UK as in most of northern Europe, organic crop yields can be 40%–50% lower than conventional, more intensive farming and labour use can be 10%–25% higher.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] An Organic Aid Scheme came into effect in 1994, providing grants to fund farmers wishing to convert to organic farming.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] By the end of 1997 about 30,000 hectares (74,000 acres) had been converted under the scheme, at a cost of £750,000.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The global market for organic food was worth £1.2 billion a year (2009) and is increasing.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The UK's share of the European organic farming market was about 10%.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] DEFRA's *National statistics Organic farming statistics 2022,* published 25 May 2023, state that 509,000 hectares are farmed organically in the UK by 5,500 operators.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The figures include land under conversion to organic status.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The total organic land is approximately 3% of total farmed land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The largest component was 61.8% of UK organic land in permanent pasture (314,000 hectares).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Only 3.1% of UK cattle were raised organically.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Cereal growing represented 9.7% of organic land use (49,000 hectares).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] There has been a 31.6% decrease in organic land use since peaking in 2008.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] However, the Soil Association is optimistic that an increased organic area is to be anticipated.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] DEFRA supports organic farming by offering leaflet advice as to the compatible schemes and grants that generate income.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] *Payments for organic farmers,* published June 2023, lists five separate possibilities.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Local government authorities have powers under the Smallholdings and Allotments Act 1926 to buy and rent land to people who want to become farmers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Fifty county councils and unitary authorities in England and Wales offer tenancies on smallholdings (called "county farms") as an entry route into agriculture, but this provision is shrinking.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Between 1984 and 2006, the amount of land available as county farms shrank from 137,664 hectares (340,180 acres) to 96,206 hectares (237,730 acres), a reduction of 30%.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The number of tenants on these smallholdings shrank by 58% in the same period to about 2,900.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] County farms yielded an operational surplus of £10.6 million to local authorities in the financial year 2008–9.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Some local authorities dispose of county farms to obtain capital receipts.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Somerset County Council proposes to sell 35 of its 62 county farms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] As of March 2009, 39% of county farms were of 50 acres (20 ha) or smaller, 31% of 50 acres (20 ha) to 100 acres (40 ha) and 30% of 100 acres (40 ha) or more.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The Secretary of State for DEFRA is required to present to Parliament statistics for the English local authorities' smallholdings estates.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Incomplete but statistically significant data were presented for the fiscal year ended 31 March 2021.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] This report indicates that of 67,699 hectares held, 65,932 hectares were let as smallholdings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] It was estimated that this represents a 0.4% decline in area over a year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Arable farming was the predominant type of farming (27.6%).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] 1,978 smallholdings were let as at 31 March 2021 at an average rent per hectare of £310.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] There were 1,416 tenants of whom 69% had farm business tenancies without security of tenure, and 20% had lifetime tenancies held under the Agricultural Holdings Act 1986 with security of tenure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] As at 31 March 2021 the total rent roll for smallholdings reported was approximately £20 million.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Local authority smallholdings in Wales are the subject of annual public reports made by the Welsh Ministers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The report for 1 April 2021 to 31 March 2022 Just under 1% of total 1.9 M hectares Welsh farm land was held as smallholdings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] At 31 March 2022 there were 884 tenants holding 969 tenancies.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] 62% of the tenancies were under 20 hectares.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Total income to the landlords amounted to approximately £4.3M with an operational surplus of £2.7M.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Smallholdings in Scotland, can be either owner-occupied or tenanted holdings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] A Scottish smallholding is averagely 20 hectares in extent.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] There are approximately 20,000 smallholders.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] 75 are tenants of the Scottish Government under the Small Landholdings Acts 1886–1931.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The remainder are mostly crofters governed by the crofting legislation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Notable smallholder Michael Forbes was able to prevent Donald Trump's ambitions for a golf course in Aberdeenshire.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The 1988 salmonella in eggs scandal forced junior health minister Edwina Currie out of office two weeks after she declared that most British egg production was affected by salmonella.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The public believed her, and 4 million hens and 40 million eggs were destroyed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Years later, *The Daily Telegraph* claimed there had been a Government cover-up, and that Mrs Currie was right.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] At the height of the BSE "mad cow disease" scare in May 1990, Agriculture Minister John Gummer went on camera feeding his four year old daughter a beef burger as part of his attempt to reassure the public that eating beef was safe.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Consequently described by the BBC as "probably the most derided politician to emerge out of the BSE scandal," Gummer had been responsible for delaying a ban on beef offal in 1989.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] Subsidy payments under the Single Payments Scheme due to farmers were not made because the Rural Payments Agency had underestimated their task and had seriously underestimated the cost of their intended new computer system.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] By January 2005, thousands of farmers were unpaid: they exchanged via the NFU forthright views with the Rural Affairs Minister, Lord Bach.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] By March 2006, money still had not been paid, so the Chief Executive Johnson McNeil was removed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In the midst of the crisis, staff of the Newcastle office of the RPA were reported by the local Evening Chronicle for being captured on CCTV leaping naked between the office filing cabinets.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] On 12 June 2006, apparently to celebrate their infamy, team members and managers held a drink-and-sex-fuelled party, news of which was reported the following day in considerable detail, alongside a series of apparently leaked office emails in which farmers were referred to in unflattering terms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The *Farmers' Weekly* followed both the payments and the sex scandal narratives.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The new Chief Executive (the third inside a year) Tony Cooper hastened to investigate.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] In early August there were 4 sackings and 5 disciplinary warnings, and an admission that there had been "incidents of misbehaviour that are simply unacceptable in this organisation".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/agriculture-in-the-united-kingdom-p02] The 2007 United Kingdom foot-and-mouth outbreak caused the destruction of over 2,000 animals and the payment of £47 million damages by the government after contaminated effluent escaped from the biological research laboratories at the Pirbright Institute.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] The **Anglo-Scottish border** is a land boundary that separates the countries of England and Scotland on the island of Great Britain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] It runs for 96 miles (154 km) between Marshall Meadows Bay on the east coast and the Solway Firth in the west.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] The Firth of Forth was the border between the Picto-Gaelic Kingdom of Alba and the Anglian Kingdom of Northumbria in the early 10th century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] It became the first Anglo-Scottish border with the annexation of Northumbria by Anglo-Saxon England in the mid-10th century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] In 973, the Scottish king Kenneth II attended the English king Edgar the Peaceful at Edgar's council in Chester.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] After Kenneth had reportedly done homage, Edgar rewarded Kenneth by granting him Lothian.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Despite this transaction, the control of Lothian was not finally settled and the region was taken by the Scots at the Battle of Carham in 1018 and the River Tweed became the *de facto* Anglo-Scottish border.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] The Solway–Tweed line was legally established in 1237 by the Treaty of York between England and Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] It remains the border today, with the exception of the Debatable Lands, north of Carlisle, and a small area around Berwick-upon-Tweed, which was taken by England in 1482.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Berwick was not fully annexed into England until 1746, by the Wales and Berwick Act 1746.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] For centuries until the Union of the Crowns, the region on either side of the boundary was a lawless territory suffering from the repeated raids in each direction of the Border Reivers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] The age of marriage under Scots law is 16, while it is 18 under English law.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] The border settlements of Gretna Green to the west, and Coldstream and Lamberton to the east, were convenient for elopers from England who wanted to marry under Scottish laws, and marry without publicity.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] The land border is near and roughly parallel to the 420 million-year-old Iapetus Suture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] This expansion was driven by Norman, Breton, and Flemish forces encouraged by both Norman England and Alba, who dispossessed and colonised lands of Strathclyde, Galloway and Lothian to Northumbria, Cumberland (Cumbria), and Westmorland (Westmoringas).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Previously, this broad region had been a complex mosaic of Brythonic, Anglian, Gaelic—including Norse and Norse-Gael communities and polities.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] The border country, historically known as the Scottish Marches, is the area on either side of the Anglo-Scottish border including parts of the modern council areas of Dumfries and Galloway and the Scottish Borders, and parts of the English counties of Cumbria and Northumberland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] It is a hilly area, with the Scottish Southern Uplands to the north, and the Cheviot Hills forming the border between the two countries to the south.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] In 1333, during the Second War of Scottish Independence, Scotland was defeated at the Battle of Halidon Hill and Edward III occupied much of the borderlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Edward declared Edward Balliol the new King of Scots, in exchange for much of southern Scotland and absolute supplication, but this was not recognised by the majority of the Scottish nobility who remained loyal to David II and conflict continued.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] By 1341, Perth and Edinburgh had been retaken by the Scots and Edward Balliol fled to England, effectively nullifying the supposed treaty.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Edward would continue the war but would be unable to restore the puppet ruler Balliol to the throne and with the Treaty of Berwick (1357) Scottish independence was once again acknowledged with any pretence to territorial annexations dropped.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] A 16th-century Act of the Scottish Parliament talks about the chiefs of the border clans, and a late 17th-century statement by the Lord Advocate uses the terms "clan" and "family" interchangeably.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Although Lowland aristocrats may have increasingly liked to refer to themselves as "families", the idea that the term "clan" should be used for Highland families alone is a 19th-century convention.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] This interchangeability, however, is conditional rather than automatic: Agnew and the Lord Lyon's own guidance both state that a clan or family is a legally recognised "noble incorporation" only once it has a chief recognised by the Lord Lyon.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] A name group without a recognised chief has no equivalent legal standing under either label.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] For centuries the Marches on either side of the boundary was an area of mixed allegiances, where families or clans switched which country or side they supported as suited their family interests at that time, and lawlessness abounded.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Before the personal union of the two kingdoms under James, the border clans would switch allegiance between the Scottish and English crowns depending on what was most favourable for the members of the clan.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] For a time a powerful local clan dominated a region on the border between England and Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] It was known as the Debatable Lands and neither monarch's writ was heeded.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Following the 1603 Union of the Crowns, King James VI & I decreed that the Borders should be renamed "the Middle Shires".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] In the same year the King placed George Home, 1st Earl of Dunbar in charge of the pacification of the borders.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Courts were set up in the towns of the Middle Shires and known reivers were arrested.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] The more troublesome and lower classes were executed without trial; known as "Jeddart justice" (after the town of Jedburgh in Roxburghshire).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Mass hanging soon became a common occurrence.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] In 1605 he established a joint commission of ten members, drawn equally from Scotland and England, to bring law and order to the region.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] This was aided by statutes in 1606 and 1609, first to repeal hostile laws on both sides of the border, and then to more easily prosecute cross-border raiders.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Reivers could no longer escape justice by crossing from England to Scotland or vice versa.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] The rough-and-ready Border Laws were abolished and the folk of the middle shires found they had to obey the law of the land like all other subjects.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] In 1607 James felt he could boast that "the Middle Shires" had "become the navel or umbilic of both kingdoms, planted and peopled with civility and riches".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] After ten years King James had succeeded; the Middle Shires had been brought under central law and order.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] By the early 1620s the Borders were so peaceful that the Crown was able to scale down its operations.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Despite these improvements, the Joint Commission continued its work, and as late as 25 September 1641 under King Charles I, Sir Richard Graham, a local laird and English MP, was petitioning the Parliament of Scotland "for regulating the disorders in the borders".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Conditions along the border generally deteriorated during the Commonwealth and Protectorate periods, with the development of Moss-trooper raiders.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Following the Restoration, ongoing border lawlessness was dealt with by reviving former legislation, renewed continually in eleven subsequent acts, for periods ranging from five to eleven years, up until the late 1750s.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] The Debatable Lands lay between Scotland and England to the north of Carlisle, the largest population centre being Canonbie.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] For over three hundred years the area was effectively controlled by local clans, such as the Armstrongs, who successfully resisted any attempt by the Scottish or English governments to impose their authority.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] In 1552 commissioners met to divide the land in two: Douglas of Drumlanrigg leading the Scots; Lord Wharton leading the English; the French ambassador acting as umpire.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] The Scots' Dike was built as the new frontier, with stones set up bearing the arms of England and of Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Berwick is famous for its hesitation over whether it is part of Scotland or England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Berwickshire is in Scotland while the town is in England, although both Berwick and the lands up to the Firth of Forth belonged to the Kingdom of Northumbria in the Early Middle Ages.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] The town changed hands more than a dozen times before being finally taken by the English in 1482, though confusion continued for centuries.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] The Wales and Berwick Act 1746 clarified the status of Berwick as an English town.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] In the 1950s the artist Wendy Wood moved the border signs south to the middle of the River Tweed as a protest.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] In 2008 SNP MSP Christine Grahame made calls in the Scottish Parliament for Berwick to become part of Scotland again.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] At the River Tweed the border runs down the middle of the river, however between the villages of Wark and Cornhill the Scottish border comes south of the river to enclose a small riverside meadow of approximately 2 to 3 acres (about a hectare).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] It is said locally that every year the men of Coldstream (to the North of the river) would play mob football with the men of Wark (to the South of the river) at Ba, and the winning side would claim the Ba Green for their country.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] As Coldstream grew to have a larger population than Wark, the Coldstream men always defeated the Wark men at the game, and so the land became a permanent part of Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] It is a common misconception that Hadrian's Wall marks the Anglo-Scottish border.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] The wall lies entirely within England and has never formed this boundary.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] While in the west, at Bowness-on-Solway, it is less than 0.6 mi (1.0 km) south of the border with Scotland, in the east it is as much as 68 miles (109 km) away.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] For centuries the wall was the boundary between the Roman province of *Britannia* (to the south) and the Celtic lands of *Caledonia* (to the north).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] However *Britannia* occasionally extended as far north as the later Antonine Wall.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Furthermore, to speak of England and Scotland at any time prior to the ninth century is anachronistic; such nations had no meaningful existence during the period of Roman rule.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] "Hadrian's Wall" is nonetheless sometimes used as an informal reference to the modern border, often semi-humorously.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Cumbria and Northumberland have among the largest Scottish-born communities in the world outside Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] 16,628 Scottish-born people were residing in Cumbria in 2001 (3.41% of the county's population) and 11,435 Scottish-born people were residing in Northumberland (3.72% of the county's population); the overall percentage of Scottish-born people in England is 1.62%.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/anglo-scottish-border] Consequently, almost 9% of Scotland's population is English-born (459,486), with higher than average percentages of English-born people in both Dumfries & Galloway and the Scottish Borders council areas, respectively, reaching as high as 35% or higher English-born.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The **Antonine Wall** (Latin: *Vallum Antonini*) was a turf fortification on stone foundations, built by the Romans across what is now the Central Belt of Scotland, between the Firth of Clyde and the Firth of Forth.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Built some twenty years after Hadrian's Wall to the south, and intended to supersede it, while it was garrisoned it was the northernmost frontier barrier of the Roman Empire.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] It spanned approximately 63 kilometres (39 miles) and was about 3 metres (10 feet) high and 5 metres (16 feet) wide.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Lidar scans have been carried out to establish the length of the wall and the Roman distance units used.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Security was bolstered by a deep ditch on the northern side.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] It is thought that there was a wooden palisade on top of the turf.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The barrier was the second of two "great walls" created by the Romans in Great Britain in the second century AD.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Its ruins are less evident than those of the better-known and longer Hadrian's Wall to the south, primarily because the turf and wood wall has largely weathered away, unlike its stone-built southern predecessor.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Construction began in AD 142 at the order of Roman Emperor Antoninus Pius.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Estimates of how long it took to complete vary widely, with six and twelve years most commonly proposed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Antoninus Pius never visited Britain, unlike his predecessor Hadrian.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Pressure from the Caledonians probably led Antoninus to send the empire's troops farther north.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The Antonine Wall was protected by 16 forts with small fortlets between them; troop movement was facilitated by a road linking all the sites known as the Military Way.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The soldiers who built the wall commemorated the construction and their struggles with the Caledonians with decorative slabs, twenty of which survive.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The wall was abandoned only eight years after completion, and the garrisons relocated rearward to Hadrian's Wall.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Most of the wall and its associated fortifications have been destroyed over time, but some remains are visible.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Many of these have come under the care of Historic Environment Scotland and the UNESCO World Heritage Committee.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The Roman Emperor Antoninus Pius ordered the construction of the Antonine Wall around 142.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Quintus Lollius Urbicus, governor of Roman Britain at the time, initially supervised the effort, which may have taken as long as twelve years.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The wall stretches 63 kilometres (39 miles) from Old Kilpatrick in West Dunbartonshire on the Firth of Clyde to Carriden near Bo'ness on the Firth of Forth.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The wall was intended to extend Roman territory and dominance by replacing Hadrian's Wall 160 kilometres (100 miles) to the south, as the frontier of *Britannia*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] But while the Romans did establish forts and temporary camps further north of the Antonine Wall in order to protect their routes to northern Britain, they did not conquer the Caledonians, and the Antonine Wall suffered many attacks.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The Romans called the land north of the wall *Caledonia*, though in some contexts the term may refer to the whole area north of Hadrian's Wall.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The land north of the Antonine Wall became known as Albany after the settlement of the Gaels in the 6th century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The Antonine Wall was shorter than Hadrian's Wall and built of turf on a stone foundation, but it was still an impressive achievement.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] It was also a simpler fortification than Hadrian's Wall insofar as it did not have a subsidiary ditch system (Vallum) behind it to the south.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] As built, the wall was typically a bank, about three metres (10 feet) high, made of layered turves and occasionally earth with a wide ditch on the north side, and a military way on the south.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The stone foundations and wing walls of the original forts on the Antonine Wall demonstrate that the original plan was to build a stone wall similar to Hadrian's Wall, but this was quickly amended.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The Romans initially planned to build forts every 10 kilometres (6 miles), but this was soon revised to every 3.3 kilometres (2 miles), resulting in a total of nineteen forts along the wall.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The best preserved but also one of the smallest forts is Rough Castle Fort.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] In addition to the forts, there are at least nine smaller fortlets, very likely on Roman mile spacings, which formed part of the original scheme, some of which were later replaced by forts.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The most visible fortlet is Kinneil, at the eastern end of the Wall, near Bo'ness.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] There was once a remarkable Roman structure within sight of the Antonine Wall at Stenhousemuir, which took its name from the Roman "stone house".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] This was Arthur's O'on, a circular stone domed monument or rotunda, which might have been a temple, or a *tropaeum*, a victory monument.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] It was demolished for its stone in 1743, though a replica exists at Penicuik House.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] In addition to the line of the Wall itself there are a number of coastal forts both in the East (e.g.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Inveresk) and West (Outerwards and Lurg Moor), which should be considered as outposts and/or supply bases to the Wall itself.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] In addition a number of forts further north were brought back into service in the Gask Ridge area, including Ardoch, Strageath, Bertha (Perth) and probably Dalginross and Cargill.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Recent research by Glasgow University has shown that the distance stones, stone sculptures unique to the Antonine Wall which were embedded in the wall to mark the lengths built by each legion, were brightly painted unlike their present bare appearance.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] These stones are preserved in the university's museum and are said to be the best-preserved examples of statuary from any Roman frontier.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Several of the slabs have been analysed by various techniques including portable X-ray fluorescence (pXRF).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Tiny remnants of paint have been detected by surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Several of the distance slabs have been scanned and 3-D videos produced.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] There are plans to reproduce the slabs, both digitally and in real physical copies, with their authentic colours.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] A copy of the Bridgeness Slab has already been made and can be found in Bo'ness.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] It is also expected that lottery funding will allow replicas of distance markers to be placed along the length of the wall.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The wall was abandoned within two decades of completion when the Roman legions withdrew to Hadrian's Wall in 162, and over time may have reached an accommodation with the Brythonic tribes of the area, whom they may have fostered as possible buffer states which would later become "The Old North".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] After a series of attacks in 197, the emperor Septimius Severus arrived in Scotland in 208, and campaigned against the Maeatae (based in the central Midland Valley on either side of the Firth of Clyde – Firth of Forth line) and the Caledonians to their north.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] While he carried out substantial work on Hadrian's Wall at the time, there is no evidence of any attention being paid to the remains of the Antonine Wall during the campaigns of 208–210.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] References in Late Roman sources to Severus' wall-building activities led to later scholars like Bede mistaking references to the Antonine Wall for ones to Hadrian's Wall.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] In the centuries that the Antonine Wall has lain abandoned, it has influenced culture between the Forth and the Clyde.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Bede associated Gildas's turf wall with the Antonine Wall.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Bede obviously identified Gildas's stone wall as Hadrian's Wall, but he sets its construction in the 5th century rather than the 120s, and does not mention Hadrian.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] And he would appear to have believed that the ditch-and-mound barrier known as the Vallum (just to the south of, and contemporary with, Hadrian's Wall) was the rampart constructed by Severus.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Many centuries would pass before just who built what became apparent.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] In medieval histories, such as the chronicles of John of Fordun, the wall is called *Gryme's dyke*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Fordun says that the name came from the grandfather of the imaginary king Eugenius son of Farquahar.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] This evolved over time into Graham's dyke – a name still found in Bo'ness at the wall's eastern end – and then linked with Clan Graham.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Of note is that Graeme in some parts of Scotland is a nickname for the devil, and Gryme's Dyke would thus be the Devil's Dyke, mirroring the name of the Roman limes in Southern Germany often called 'Teufelsmauer'.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Grímr and Grim are bynames for Odin or Wodan, who might be credited with the wish to build earthworks in unreasonably short periods of time.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] This name is the same one found as Grim's Ditch several times in England in connection with early ramparts: for example, near Wallingford, Oxfordshire or between Berkhamsted (Herts) and Bradenham (Bucks).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Other names used by antiquarians include the Wall of Pius and the Antonine Vallum, after Antoninus Pius.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Edmund Spenser in Book II of *The Faerie Queene* (1590) alludes to the Wall, misattributing it to Constantine II.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Hector Boece in his 1527 *History of Scotland* called it the "wall of Abercorn", repeating the story that it had been destroyed by Graham.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Renaissance patrons in the 16th century, including George Keith, 5th Earl Marischal, who were exposed to the world of international scholarship through diplomacy, began to collect antiquities.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The Earl Marischal set a stone from the Antonine Wall in the walls of Dunnotar Castle and had it painted and gilded, probably by Andrew Melville of Stonehaven.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The stone is now at the Hunterian Museum in Glasgow and residual paint traces probably remaining from its later reuse have been analysed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The UK government's nomination of the Antonine Wall for World Heritage status to the international conservation body UNESCO was first officially announced in 2003.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] It has been backed by the Scottish Government since 2005 and by Scotland's then Culture Minister Patricia Ferguson since 2006.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] It became the UK's official nomination in late January 2007, and MSPs were called to support the bid anew in May 2007.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The Antonine Wall was listed as an extension to the World Heritage Site "Frontiers of the Roman Empire" on 7 July 2008.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Though the Antonine Wall is mentioned in the text, it does not appear on UNESCO's map of world heritage properties.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Several individual sites along the line of the wall are in the care of Historic Environment Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] All sites are unmanned and open at all reasonable times.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The first capable effort to systematically map the Antonine Wall was undertaken in 1764 by William Roy, the forerunner of the Ordnance Survey.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] He provided accurate and detailed drawings of its remains, and where the wall has been destroyed by later development, his maps and drawings are now the only reliable record of it.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] In the 19th century, the Ordnance Survey showed the visible traces of the wall in some detail on its first- and second-edition maps at 25-inch and 6-inch scales, but no attempt was made then to undertake archaeological work.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Sir George Macdonald carried out systematic work on the wall that was published in 1911 and in an expanded second edition in 1934.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] His work provided the basis for a large-scale (25-inch) folio produced by the Ordnance Survey in 1931.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] The Ordnance Survey produced a revised folio in 1954–1957, and then carried out a new complete survey in 1979–80.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] They also published a smaller-scale map of the Wall, at 1:25,000 in 1969.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Further mapping activity was carried out to support the nomination of the Wall as a World Heritage Site.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland/antonine-wall] Modern computer techniques like using GIS and LIDAR can now map the wall in three dimensions, making it much easier to study, for example, how visible forts and fortlets were to those at their neighbouring stations along the wall.
